WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:11.000
Where are we running?

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:14.000
You want to, is that bag not in the way?

00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:20.000
It's not, but it is better to keep it down.

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:22.000
Okay.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:24.000
Look, we are rolling.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:30.000
This is Emilye Crosby with the Southern Oral History Program at the University of North Carolina Chapel Hill.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:35.000
And this morning's oral history is part of the Civil Rights History Project,

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:41.000
which is sponsored by the Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of African American History and Culture,

00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:44.000
and the American Folklife Center in the Library of Congress.

00:00:44.000 --> 00:00:52.000
Today is June 27, 2013, and we're in Silver Spring, Maryland with Mr. Luis Zapata at his home.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:54.000
And with me is John Bishop.

00:00:54.000 --> 00:00:57.000
Thanks so much for joining us this morning.

00:00:57.000 --> 00:00:58.000
Thank you.

00:00:58.000 --> 00:00:59.000
Whether it's a great thing to do.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:04.000
Can you start by telling me about your family and where you grew up?

00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:13.000
Well, I grew up in Orange County, California, at the home of the crew, not at the home of the John Bird Society.

00:01:13.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Sorry.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:17.000
I was moving ahead too far.

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:20.000
The John Birch Society is right when you can get.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:26.000
My folks were, I guess, liberal Democrats, you probably say.

00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:32.000
And I grew up until I left out when I was really young, and had no idea about politics.

00:01:32.000 --> 00:01:37.000
So all that came much later in my, or later in my life, not much later.

00:01:37.000 --> 00:01:39.000
What kind of work did your parents do?

00:01:39.000 --> 00:01:42.000
My father was an engineer.

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:48.000
He always had trouble because it's a mechanical engineer.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:58.000
And, you know, my father had let me know, and my mother's anglo, and so he had some trouble with that in jobs and stuff like that.

00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:04.000
My mother owned a yarn shop when on and off and taught knitting and things like that,

00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:08.000
so not someone crocheting and crew work.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:12.000
And I remember about growing up over some of the things that shaped your life.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:14.000
Oh.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:16.000
Goodness.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:25.000
Getting beat up as a kid, coming home from school, you know, for, and there wasn't a large Latino population in the community.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:32.000
And, and I remembered having lots of problems, and, yeah, that's the, mm-hmm.

00:02:33.000 --> 00:02:44.000
Lots of problems, and until I learned to fight back, and, and eventually, I just, I went off and actually left home for a young, came back, left home for a young.

00:02:44.000 --> 00:02:52.000
You know, there was, finding about the ladies and stuff like that, and, you know, what young men do.

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:59.000
Was, how did your family deal with racial cultural identity in that context?

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:01.000
They didn't address it at all.

00:03:01.000 --> 00:03:04.000
It was not talked about, it was not addressed, it was not anything.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:08.000
So you were sort of on your own to figure that out.

00:03:08.000 --> 00:03:15.000
And, um, I remember my brother was dating somebody, and her mother said, no, you can't.

00:03:15.000 --> 00:03:24.000
And, uh, because, to the daughter, and nobody ever talked about it, it just was accepted, that's the sort of thing that happened.

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.000
So, I'm sorry, he couldn't date.

00:03:27.000 --> 00:03:29.000
Oh, the mother of his person.

00:03:29.000 --> 00:03:32.000
Yeah, the young lady's mother said, okay, not your mother.

00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:33.000
I will not have that.

00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
And, she said, I'm sorry, but I can't do it.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:40.000
And, that's, you know, that was standard back then.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:42.000
We're talking about in the 50s.

00:03:42.000 --> 00:03:43.000
Yeah.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:46.000
And so, and he was older than I was.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:49.000
Yeah. Did you and your brother talk about it at all?

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:50.000
Or was it all just flu?

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:51.000
No, no, we didn't talk about it.

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:52.000
Yeah.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:56.000
He had his problems, and he still does, and I, you know, I just leave it be.

00:03:56.000 --> 00:03:57.000
Yeah.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:03:59.000
So, you say you left home fairly young.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:01.000
What did you do when you left home?

00:04:01.000 --> 00:04:03.000
Well, I started working.

00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:07.000
I think I was about 10, 9 or 10.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:14.000
And I'd work in people's gardens and make money, and I had a paper route, and then I'd work on boats and scrape boats, because I could swim.

00:04:14.000 --> 00:04:19.000
I'd dive down, you go into boat, and you scrape the seaweed off and stuff.

00:04:19.000 --> 00:04:31.000
And then some of my friends and I would, there were tour boats that would go out from Newport Beach, and they would throw quarters, and we'd dive down and get quarters, and that sort of thing.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:37.000
Tell I burst my ear drums, too, when I was a kid.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:46.000
And from there, I became a dishwasher and a bus boy, and then I learned to be a short-order cook, and actually being a short-order cook is something, and eventually a chef.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:53.000
I worked all over the country, and if I was traveling, somebody needed somebody, and you can always find job as a short-order cook.

00:04:53.000 --> 00:05:05.000
And if you know how to do it, you can eat a whole day's worth of food in an eight-hour shift, and, you know, something don't pay you that much, you don't still don't have a food bill.

00:05:05.000 --> 00:05:09.000
It sounds like you've picked up quite a few handy skills over the years.

00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:14.000
Yeah, and I guess working, my mother taught me to knit, when I was, I think I didn't knit.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:18.000
I don't know how old I was, my first slippers. I had to knit, much slippers, knit them.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:31.000
And I become a craftsman, that's not on my biography for some reason, but a lot of the stuff you see around here, I made myself, I do Native American craft work and other craft work.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:36.000
I was making sandals and selling them, can't make a living as a crafts person, so.

00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:45.000
But, you know, my hands are good enough, so I was a carpenter and a cabinet maker over the years, and done things with my hands.

00:05:45.000 --> 00:05:50.000
How did you get involved in movement work?

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:57.000
Well, I really guess it happened, I went to San Jose State College, and that's probably where I really learned about politics.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:10.000
I was liberal, I remember being some kid in school, called me a communist in elementary school or high school, named this junior high, in Newport Beach, and I didn't even know what a communist meant.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:14.000
But I started to understand politics and get involved in politics.

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:18.000
I went to school first as a physics major, what that was about.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:26.000
But I didn't fit it in very well with the physics majors, but I became at San Jose, and that was during all the things were happening at Berkeley.

00:06:26.000 --> 00:06:36.000
And I became politicized and got more politicized, it was involved in, you know, invasion of the Dominican Republic and all those things.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:46.000
And then I went to work with farm workers, and, um, get organized, you know, working the fields.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:54.000
So did you, when you went to San Jose State, was that part of a, you know, was that a regular sort of trajectory or out of graduate high school, go right into college?

00:06:54.000 --> 00:06:57.000
Well, I wasn't, I mean, there was some spaces because I was working.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:04.000
But yes, my, the objective was I'd get a degree in physics, and I, I'd become a normal person, and that never happened.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:06.000
And being an engineer, or something.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:09.000
No person never did happen, you know, that couldn't happen.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:15.000
Or, you know, some sort of scientist. I think I wanted to be an astronaut or something at one point in life.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:23.000
And, but that, you know, I can tell all sorts of stories, but the physics majors, I couldn't even talk to them.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:29.000
They just, they lived in a whole different world. I was worried about social issues, and they didn't know what a social issue was.

00:07:29.000 --> 00:07:32.000
You didn't think about changing your major, you just went for the...

00:07:32.000 --> 00:07:49.000
I actually, of course, dropped out. I was with farm workers and the story behind that is, they had started the Mississippi Freedom Labor Union, and, and somebody at, it may have been Lee Bankhead, who was the head of Mississippi Freedom Labor Union under Kofo.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:54.000
I don't know who contacted Chavez, but Chavez said, meeting anybody want to go to Mississippi.

00:07:54.000 --> 00:07:56.000
And I said, what the heck, a campaign?

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:02.000
Yeah, we were here because we were getting beaten up all the time by the guy. I didn't know they were going to shoot at us in Mississippi. Damn.

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:05.000
But anyway, I stuck up my hand. Next thing I know I was in Mississippi.

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:06.000
Well, and...

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:08.000
So I didn't, I dropped out of college.

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:09.000
Okay.

00:08:09.000 --> 00:08:17.000
And it wasn't until, oh, probably the 80s or the 90s, I went back and eventually got it, and I didn't go back in physics.

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:19.000
I got it to Green English.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:20.000
Better, sure.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:22.000
Because, then more writing than I'd done anything else.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:31.000
So, I'd like to ask a little bit more about how you got involved with the farm workers, but just to clarify,

00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:35.000
were you in school until you went to Mississippi, were you working at with the farm workers?

00:08:35.000 --> 00:08:37.000
Yeah, I was pretty much in school.

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:43.000
Yeah, I was pretty much in school, although I dropped the number of credits I was taking, so I could do more with farm workers.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:45.000
But I think I was still officially registered.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:46.000
Yeah.

00:08:46.000 --> 00:08:48.000
And then I just left.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:51.000
I said, you know, this isn't makes sense. This isn't what I want to do with my life.

00:08:51.000 --> 00:08:54.000
So how did you connect with the farm workers and become an organist?

00:08:54.000 --> 00:08:57.000
Well, they were all around, San Jose.

00:08:57.000 --> 00:09:00.000
And so they were organizing in the fields outside in San Jose.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:02.000
I mean, they were everywhere.

00:09:02.000 --> 00:09:14.000
And, and a lot of Luis Valdés, I went to school, you know, he is, La Bamba,

00:09:15.000 --> 00:09:21.000
And he became a well-known playwright, but I was already into English more than anything else.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:28.000
And I, Luis Valdez and a lot of other Latinos were involved in all sorts of politics.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And how I got into it, I mean, it's just was like the Civil Rights Movement.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:34.000
It was in the air.

00:09:34.000 --> 00:09:40.000
I mean, you know, there was no major struggle like there was in the South,

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:48.000
but in terms of African Civil Rights, African-American Civil Rights in San Jose,

00:09:48.000 --> 00:09:53.000
because San Jose at that time had the largest Latino population north of the border.

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:55.000
It was larger than it was in L.A.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:09:57.000
So, you know, it's just normal.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:10:02.000
So did was, did, did becoming, did working with the farm workers,

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:08.000
did that then give you a space to be Latino in a different way after sort of it,

00:10:08.000 --> 00:10:10.000
not being addressed in your family?

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:14.000
It's interesting.

00:10:14.000 --> 00:10:16.000
I mean, I didn't thought about that.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:18.000
Probably I was moving into that.

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:24.000
And, interestingly enough, of course, there wasn't any space to do that in Mississippi.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:29.000
And it just, I'm not to jump through history.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:37.000
It was after I came out, of course, one of the things that was happening in the Afro-American movement

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:40.000
is they were looking to the dyspora and back to Africa.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:48.000
And I started to focus on, after Mississippi, not so much the Latino,

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:55.000
but the Native American issues, because we are most Native people.

00:10:55.000 --> 00:10:58.000
The brown comes, doesn't come from the few Africans.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:01.000
And there were a lot of Africans that were brought to Mexico and other areas,

00:11:01.000 --> 00:11:05.000
and especially Cuba and places, but most of it comes from Native people.

00:11:05.000 --> 00:11:11.000
Although it's colonized enough that they don't focus on that,

00:11:11.000 --> 00:11:16.000
but usually I am, in fact, supposed to be a letter published in the post,

00:11:16.000 --> 00:11:21.000
Russian post, I just wrote about that and folks not paying attention to it.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.000
That it's a Native American issue.

00:11:23.000 --> 00:11:24.000
Yeah.

00:11:24.000 --> 00:11:26.000
The...

00:11:26.000 --> 00:11:28.000
Whoops.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:29.000
Am I supposed to repeat anything?

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:30.000
I don't know what I said.

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:33.000
I saw a periodically too close the file.

00:11:33.000 --> 00:11:34.000
Oh, okay.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:36.000
Yeah, understood.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:39.000
So, what kind of...

00:11:39.000 --> 00:11:43.000
Tell me about organizing with the farm workers.

00:11:43.000 --> 00:11:46.000
Well, I was a kid.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:49.000
And I was a kid when I went to Mississippi in terms of experience.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
I became a fairly good organizer, I think.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
I'm now considered a pretty good organizer.

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:56.000
But we were just...

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:59.000
We told Gwauten the Field and go join the workers,

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:04.000
and then convince them, because there'd be people yelling and screaming saying,

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:07.000
you know, come on strike, join us, Welga, et cetera.

00:12:07.000 --> 00:12:13.000
And so I was supposed to join in the fields and then convince people who were working around me

00:12:13.000 --> 00:12:16.000
to go join and get a whole bunch and we'd walk out on strike.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:21.000
And usually it was one or two or three of us who were doing that.

00:12:21.000 --> 00:12:27.000
The people who had been working for a long time doing it were known by the cops

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:28.000
and known...

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:34.000
And a lot of times the cops weren't there, but the thugs that went plantations,

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.000
they were farms.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:40.000
The farms, the thugs knew who were the organizers,

00:12:40.000 --> 00:12:42.000
and they wouldn't let them under the field.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:45.000
But since they needed hands, you could go in and say,

00:12:45.000 --> 00:12:47.000
I'm just in Address and Raggedy clothes.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:12:53.000
And I'd go in and they let me in there, then the main idea was we'd take people out.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:12:59.000
We'd leave people out on strike, because we were trying to do this strike.

00:12:59.000 --> 00:13:00.000
There were other things happening.

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:03.000
There was a grape strike, of course, which was PR.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:06.000
I mean, that was all about getting to the median, making speeches.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:07.000
But I was just as young kid.

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:08.000
I didn't know what I was doing.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:09.000
So you...

00:13:09.000 --> 00:13:12.000
So the grape strikes going on, but is this a different strike?

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:13.000
There was also...

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:15.000
I usually worked on the strawberry strike.

00:13:15.000 --> 00:13:19.000
I mean, they were working for higher wages.

00:13:20.000 --> 00:13:24.000
I even worked one time on Sparigas boys, and Sparigas hard to pick.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:26.000
Each little thing with this little hook and I...

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:27.000
God.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:30.000
Even my back is a lot older now, but...

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:34.000
But no, it was getting higher wages for almost all of the things.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:39.000
But what made the media and what they were asking people all around the country

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:44.000
to boycott California grapes unless they had a unionized sticker on it.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:47.000
But I don't think...

00:13:47.000 --> 00:13:49.000
I never worked in a grape field.

00:13:49.000 --> 00:13:52.000
I never were picking grapes.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:54.000
And so when...

00:13:54.000 --> 00:13:58.000
At this meeting, when they were looking for somebody to go to Mississippi,

00:13:58.000 --> 00:14:00.000
did you have a picture of Mississippi in your head?

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:05.000
And the slightest idea when I was volunteering for young kid who thinks,

00:14:05.000 --> 00:14:06.000
oh, this...

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:07.000
That's good.

00:14:07.000 --> 00:14:10.000
I knew about, you know, black struggles, etc.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:12.000
I don't know what he was doing.

00:14:12.000 --> 00:14:14.000
No, I went down there and...

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:18.000
It was more community organizing and I got into that.

00:14:18.000 --> 00:14:21.000
And...

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:26.000
I have done lots of thinking over the years about how isolated it was that time

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:31.000
for people in the rural areas all across the South.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:36.000
TV, if you had it, the biggest news was who won the bass fishing contest.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:38.000
It was almost no national news.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:39.000
There were no national papers.

00:14:39.000 --> 00:14:41.000
You get these local papers that just talked...

00:14:41.000 --> 00:14:45.000
Again, about the bass fishing contestor, who married who?

00:14:45.000 --> 00:14:48.000
And you had no sense of...

00:14:48.000 --> 00:14:51.000
Geopolitical, certainly not other countries.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:54.000
Nothing was mentioned about other countries.

00:14:54.000 --> 00:15:00.000
And so you really didn't focus on national pictures.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:03.000
It was only until I went back...

00:15:03.000 --> 00:15:04.000
I forgot what I was...

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:06.000
Maybe on Mike Espice campaign.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:10.000
And I saw cable TV and rise up people at cable TV in their homes.

00:15:10.000 --> 00:15:12.000
And they were watching New York stations.

00:15:12.000 --> 00:15:14.000
And seeing stuff that had never...

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:19.000
Nobody would ever saw when I was there in terms of national news.

00:15:19.000 --> 00:15:26.000
We got more via SNCC channels of things happening in Africa and New York than we certainly did.

00:15:26.000 --> 00:15:27.000
To the news media.

00:15:27.000 --> 00:15:28.000
It was nothing on.

00:15:28.000 --> 00:15:30.000
Yeah.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.000
So no idea about Mississippi.

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:36.000
Did you have much sense of SNCC before you got to Mississippi?

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:42.000
No, I was a little about SNCC because they were in San Jose making speeches and stuff.

00:15:42.000 --> 00:15:49.000
I mean, I knew enough, I think to understand that SCLC was the...

00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:52.000
The middle of the road or the less militant.

00:15:52.000 --> 00:15:54.000
And by then I was getting pretty militant.

00:15:54.000 --> 00:15:59.000
And so I understood that this wasn't a fairly militant.

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:02.000
But it wasn't until I got immersed in that.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
And I began to understand the real differences.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:08.000
And what was...

00:16:08.000 --> 00:16:13.000
I don't even know if I understood what COFO was back then.

00:16:13.000 --> 00:16:15.000
It was, okay, they're starting a union.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:17.000
And I'll just going to have an help.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:20.000
And that will help all people's, etc.

00:16:20.000 --> 00:16:22.000
And yeah, I was naive.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:26.000
I mean, you know, and people like to look back and say how they were...

00:16:26.000 --> 00:16:27.000
Had great insight.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:29.000
I didn't have great insight.

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:35.000
I was working and organizing, getting people to try and join the strike

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:39.000
and doing that sort of thing and all sorts of discussions about that.

00:16:39.000 --> 00:16:41.000
We did a lot of voter registration.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:44.000
I probably spent as much of more time doing voter registration, things like that.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:48.000
Getting head start programs going and all the things.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
Everybody did everything.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:53.000
Um-hmm.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:58.000
Do you remember how you came into Mississippi?

00:16:58.000 --> 00:17:01.000
Like who you met first?

00:17:01.000 --> 00:17:05.000
Well, I think I met Lee Bankhead first, because they were waiting for me.

00:17:05.000 --> 00:17:07.000
And I had a map.

00:17:07.000 --> 00:17:11.000
And I brought down a car loaded with clothes.

00:17:11.000 --> 00:17:14.000
And it was a car that was a gift to SNCC or Kofo.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:17.000
I don't know who it was a gift to.

00:17:17.000 --> 00:17:22.000
And it was loaded with clothes for people and some other stuff.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:26.000
And I think I was alone.

00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:28.000
I don't remember.

00:17:28.000 --> 00:17:32.000
Over the years, because I actually went north a number of times

00:17:32.000 --> 00:17:34.000
or to California and did fundraising.

00:17:34.000 --> 00:17:40.000
Over the years, I think I brought three cars down, including one Hearst,

00:17:40.000 --> 00:17:43.000
which we had to tell people it was an ambulance because nobody would ride it.

00:17:43.000 --> 00:17:47.000
I was going to say that I'm a little ominous going into Mississippi with the Hearst.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:50.000
People didn't, because it had some of the stuff stripped off and it was black.

00:17:50.000 --> 00:17:53.000
But then we tell them it was an ambulance because people would say,

00:17:53.000 --> 00:17:54.000
there's big vehicles.

00:17:54.000 --> 00:17:55.000
Nobody needed seats.

00:17:55.000 --> 00:17:57.000
You just packed bodies in.

00:17:57.000 --> 00:17:59.000
I had all sorts of drivers license.

00:17:59.000 --> 00:18:01.000
I had a Mississippi driver's license.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:03.000
California driver's license.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:06.000
Some places, when I was in New York, I think I got a New York driver's license.

00:18:06.000 --> 00:18:08.000
You can have multiple drivers license back then.

00:18:08.000 --> 00:18:10.000
Now it's all computerized.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:14.000
But I had, you know, so I was always one of the drivers.

00:18:14.000 --> 00:18:17.000
And there's some funny stories about driving in the north.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:19.000
But that's okay.

00:18:19.000 --> 00:18:25.000
And so, you know, we had to tell them it was an ambulance and everybody thought it was okay.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:28.000
They could ride in it.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:30.000
Is that going to interrupt?

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:32.000
Let me show you a set of...

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:33.000
It's hard to be a movie star.

00:18:33.000 --> 00:18:35.000
You're just a blur, by the way.

00:18:35.000 --> 00:18:37.000
You're all blur.

00:18:37.000 --> 00:18:38.000
It's a small thing in the end.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:39.000
Okay, wait a minute.

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:40.000
I can see the smiles.

00:18:40.000 --> 00:18:41.000
I can see that.

00:18:41.000 --> 00:18:42.000
But...

00:18:42.000 --> 00:18:44.000
Okay, we're back.

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:50.000
A few minutes ago, you mentioned that by this time you're becoming militant.

00:18:50.000 --> 00:18:52.000
Oh, I probably was...

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:56.000
Basically, I probably was militant when I was in elementary school and didn't know it.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:58.000
What did that mean to you then?

00:19:01.000 --> 00:19:05.000
I believed in fighting back, I guess, in struggling back.

00:19:05.000 --> 00:19:13.000
Instead of just taking it and laying down, that you want to change the system if the system wasn't right.

00:19:13.000 --> 00:19:15.000
And I don't know where I got that.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:17.000
Certainly none of my folks weren't doing that.

00:19:17.000 --> 00:19:22.000
None of the friends I had when I were younger, none of them were political.

00:19:22.000 --> 00:19:25.000
In college, I met people who were doing that.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:28.000
And I was very involved with them.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:31.000
But, you know, it was just...

00:19:31.000 --> 00:19:33.000
I guess it's in my instinct.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:35.000
You know, it's just something about it.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:36.000
You have to fight back.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:37.000
Yeah.

00:19:37.000 --> 00:19:41.000
So, when you got to Mississippi, you described driving in.

00:19:41.000 --> 00:19:47.000
Do you remember how you were introduced to what SNCC and COFO were doing?

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:50.000
No.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:52.000
I think there's...

00:19:52.000 --> 00:19:54.000
And it's part of a lot of cultures.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:19:57.000
There's not a lot of talking and explaining.

00:19:57.000 --> 00:20:00.000
SNCC people tended to do more of it.

00:20:00.000 --> 00:20:08.000
But they expected, I think, a seasoned union worker who knew how to organize.

00:20:08.000 --> 00:20:11.000
And I knew a little bit how to organize and I figured it out on the run.

00:20:11.000 --> 00:20:17.000
But over my life, I've learned a lot of times people don't explain stuff.

00:20:17.000 --> 00:20:18.000
I was...

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.000
I forgot to put down iron workers.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:21.000
I had no idea.

00:20:21.000 --> 00:20:23.000
I was a union iron worker for a while.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:26.000
And that means climbing tall buildings and putting steel together.

00:20:26.000 --> 00:20:29.000
Nobody really tells you how to do it.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:32.000
You go out there and you're supposed to watch and figure it out.

00:20:32.000 --> 00:20:35.000
And the same thing I guess was true for cooking.

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:38.000
Or being a short-order cook is nobody gigging or going to class.

00:20:38.000 --> 00:20:40.000
They didn't have classes for that.

00:20:40.000 --> 00:20:42.000
And you just figure it out.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:49.000
And I would figure out how to convince people that they ought to join the union

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:51.000
and work to get higher wages.

00:20:51.000 --> 00:20:54.000
And you tell them something and that didn't work and try and tell them something else.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:21:00.000
And I learned pretty quickly it had to be usually for their personal benefit.

00:21:00.000 --> 00:21:04.000
For me, of course, it was about we need to change the system.

00:21:04.000 --> 00:21:07.000
But if I talked about changing the system, people get glassy-eyed.

00:21:07.000 --> 00:21:10.000
They just wanted to have more money on the table because they couldn't feed their kids.

00:21:10.000 --> 00:21:11.000
Right.

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:18.000
So you put things in terms of what helped them personally and how it was going to help their family,

00:21:18.000 --> 00:21:23.000
their brothers and sisters who also were chopping cotton or picking cotton.

00:21:23.000 --> 00:21:26.000
And that's how you did it.

00:21:26.000 --> 00:21:28.000
I guess I figured it out pretty well.

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:30.000
People thought I was a pretty good organizer.

00:21:30.000 --> 00:21:37.000
And I've gone on to do a lot of organizing and giving classes and organizing since then.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:42.000
Who are some of the people that you worked most closely with in Mississippi?

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:45.000
It was mostly ministers.

00:21:45.000 --> 00:21:50.000
Lee Bankhead was the head of Mississippi Freedom Labor Union.

00:21:50.000 --> 00:21:57.000
I guess on the board was Fannie Lou Hamer and Miss Ruffin and Reverend Johnson.

00:21:58.000 --> 00:21:59.000
And I'm running out of names.

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:02.000
I can see lots of faces, but I'm running out of names.

00:22:02.000 --> 00:22:05.000
There's another woman.

00:22:05.000 --> 00:22:07.000
As you notice, most of those are women.

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:10.000
If they weren't women, they were usually ministers.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:13.000
Because the men had to work generally.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:22.000
But the movement, I'd say, was carried on the back of really strong women and ministers who were willing to stand up.

00:22:22.000 --> 00:22:24.000
And that was a great deal.

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:28.000
I expect because ministers couldn't get fired by the white establishment.

00:22:28.000 --> 00:22:33.000
Everybody else basically worked for Mr. Charlie.

00:22:33.000 --> 00:22:40.000
And so if you wanted to, and people would get fired for trying to register to vote or for organizing.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:45.000
And so, those are the people who made the decisions.

00:22:45.000 --> 00:22:48.000
And you probably know about, enough about SNCC,

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:53.000
that it is a bottom up.

00:22:53.000 --> 00:22:55.000
I mean, it's grassroots organization.

00:22:55.000 --> 00:23:03.000
And it's not like, and I don't want to disparage any of the other civil rights organizations that were top down.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:09.000
And some of those leaders have now very famous and have statues and stuff like that.

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:13.000
And they're good people, but it's a very top down decision-making process.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:16.000
SNCC was always a grassroots bottom up.

00:23:16.000 --> 00:23:22.000
And we got paid, as I recall, it was $20 a week out of which they took taxes and all that.

00:23:22.000 --> 00:23:27.000
So it was either $17 and change or $18 and change.

00:23:27.000 --> 00:23:29.000
Not a whole lot of money.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:32.000
But the reason they paid you that, and they were clear about it,

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:37.000
is if you couldn't live off the community, if people who were dirt-forward and didn't have anything,

00:23:37.000 --> 00:23:42.000
weren't willing to share their food and their enlarging, then you shouldn't be there.

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:49.000
Either the community thought you were worthwhile or get you butt out.

00:23:49.000 --> 00:23:57.000
You were telling us earlier about some of the families that you lived with in Mississippi?

00:23:57.000 --> 00:24:01.000
Oh, you were talking about, well, I stayed with them for a while.

00:24:01.000 --> 00:24:04.000
I lived with another, I wasn't mostly out of Cleveland.

00:24:04.000 --> 00:24:07.000
And so let me tell you about the shack we had in Cleveland.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:10.000
It was behind somebody's house and we could take a shower in there.

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:14.000
It had a commode in a sink behind a curtain.

00:24:14.000 --> 00:24:20.000
And that was the SNCC office in the Mississippi Freedom Labor Union office and the COFO office.

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:26.000
And it was one room when I went back years later to work on Mike S.B.'s campaign.

00:24:26.000 --> 00:24:28.000
I drove by it and saw it.

00:24:28.000 --> 00:24:30.000
It's not half as big as this room is.

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.000
I mean, it was this little teeny thing.

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:38.000
And we would, we stacked center blocks up around the bottom and we'd sleep on the floor.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:41.000
Because occasionally people come by and shoot at night and they shoot through it.

00:24:41.000 --> 00:24:43.000
And so you use the blocks as protection?

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:48.000
Yeah, we just sleep there and you know, you know, happened often enough you didn't even hardly wake up.

00:24:48.000 --> 00:24:52.000
Because they wouldn't come in. They just drive by shoot.

00:24:52.000 --> 00:24:55.000
But no, the family you were talking about.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:24:57.000
That's just one of many hundreds of stories.

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:00.000
And I mentioned that to you earlier.

00:25:00.000 --> 00:25:07.000
And some, I guess he volunteered to have somebody come and do voter registration.

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:13.000
He's black and probably about six foot ten, maybe taller.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:17.000
And he had it on plantation and he had workers on it.

00:25:17.000 --> 00:25:20.000
And he and his kids worked it too. They worked the fields.

00:25:20.000 --> 00:25:23.000
They worked their butt off.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:27.000
And I remember when I was driven out there, somebody from SNCC drove me out.

00:25:27.000 --> 00:25:34.000
And it was pitch black and I said, dogs were barking and this person comes out.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:39.000
I'm not that small. I was, you know, about six foot.

00:25:39.000 --> 00:25:41.000
I think I'm five, eleven and a half.

00:25:41.000 --> 00:25:46.000
And he gets me out of the arms and I start to go up and up and up until I'm face with somebody.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:25:48.000
I go, okay, what am I doing here?

00:25:48.000 --> 00:25:54.000
Nice guy, wonderful family. Fed me more food and I keep saying, you're done eating?

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:56.000
What's wrong, boy?

00:25:56.000 --> 00:26:00.000
They packed in so much food breakfast, which was their big meal.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:06.000
Look like Thanksgiving dinners every morning with pancakes and waffles and sausage and biscuits

00:26:06.000 --> 00:26:10.000
and hamburgers and rice and ham.

00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:13.000
And of course, they grew up and they had, you know, farm and had all those animals.

00:26:13.000 --> 00:26:17.000
But they just packed some food in and...

00:26:17.000 --> 00:26:19.000
Yes. But he'd take me every day.

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:21.000
Every morning, he went out out.

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:25.000
He was there and actually went out in the fields before sun up.

00:26:25.000 --> 00:26:33.000
And then he'd come back a little after day break and take me to groups of houses and leave me there

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:36.000
and I was trying to get these people to register to vote.

00:26:36.000 --> 00:26:40.000
Which was a standard thing to do.

00:26:40.000 --> 00:26:43.000
Not quite that way. I'd never been on a black plantation before.

00:26:43.000 --> 00:26:48.000
And he was well respected and I'd probably somewhat feared, especially in the white community,

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:52.000
yet shot gun and a rifle in the back of his pickup truck.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:26:54.000
And nobody messed with him.

00:26:54.000 --> 00:26:58.000
But yeah, that's just one of the, you know, hundreds of stories.

00:26:58.000 --> 00:27:04.000
We spent years in someplace and doing organizing and you know, whatever.

00:27:04.000 --> 00:27:08.000
I know it's hard to always remember, but do you remember where he was?

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:10.000
Like which county or town?

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:13.000
I believe it was Washington. It was maybe a sunflower.

00:27:13.000 --> 00:27:14.000
Yeah.

00:27:14.000 --> 00:27:17.000
No, I'm guessing sunflower.

00:27:17.000 --> 00:27:19.000
And it'd be interesting to research it.

00:27:19.000 --> 00:27:24.000
I've wondered about that. He probably was well known.

00:27:24.000 --> 00:27:32.000
Yeah, I'd make a nice history, but I moved on after that and I saw him at meetings occasionally.

00:27:32.000 --> 00:27:36.000
But he had a plantation to run and he worked hard.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:42.000
I mean, he took time out to get people registered and he thought that was critical to get people registered.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:45.000
And that was still during the time where you could go down. They turned your way.

00:27:45.000 --> 00:27:48.000
The voting rights act hadn't been signed at that time.

00:27:48.000 --> 00:27:53.000
And even after it was signed, that was, it took a long time to get implemented.

00:27:53.000 --> 00:27:57.000
So if you were in Cleveland, you must have spent time with Amzie Moore.

00:27:57.000 --> 00:27:58.000
Oh, sure.

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:01.000
Can you tell us what he was like?

00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:04.000
Oh.

00:28:04.000 --> 00:28:07.000
All right, goodness.

00:28:07.000 --> 00:28:12.000
Very quietly strong. I'm trying to remember.

00:28:12.000 --> 00:28:16.000
Some reason he was at a lot of meetings.

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:21.000
He usually didn't speak in churches that I can't remember.

00:28:21.000 --> 00:28:28.000
Our big thing was to get music scores, singing freedom songs and getting firebrand speakers.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:31.000
But I don't remember him speaking.

00:28:31.000 --> 00:28:35.000
He did a lot of strategizing.

00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:43.000
But I don't remember him. I was much closer to say, Fannie Mouhamer was a wonder of Miss Ruffin and people like that.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:51.000
Can you tell us about both of them?

00:28:51.000 --> 00:28:59.000
I remember Fannie Lou would get so mad she and she chewed tobacco and she gets so mad she's spitting and spitting and spitting again.

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:05.000
Everyone paid attention to her. Everyone listened to what she said.

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:12.000
She probably was as much the backbone of what happened in that part of the Delta is anybody.

00:29:12.000 --> 00:29:21.000
Her henchman was Fannie Lou was a Miss Ruffin and I have no idea what Miss Ruffin's first name is or if I ever did know.

00:29:21.000 --> 00:29:22.000
Susie.

00:29:22.000 --> 00:29:24.000
Susie. Oh, really good.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:32.000
Great lady. Between the two of them, the young guys had come in from SNCC and they always deferred.

00:29:32.000 --> 00:29:43.000
I mean, if there was an argument about or a disagreement, I might say, about how to handle, you know, whether we would work in this particular town or that particular town.

00:29:43.000 --> 00:29:48.000
Nobody ever, I mean, she'd want all the arguments between the two of them.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:51.000
So how would they do it? Would they just say what they thought?

00:29:51.000 --> 00:29:55.000
They'd say, no, that won't work. And you don't know what you're talking about.

00:29:55.000 --> 00:30:01.000
And they just bullied their way into it. Yeah, they tough ladies, tough, tough ladies.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:07.000
You said before we started filming that Ivan Ho Donaldson was a really good organizer?

00:30:07.000 --> 00:30:12.000
He did not organize in the Delta while I was there that I knew of.

00:30:12.000 --> 00:30:17.000
But in terms of tricks for organizing, you know, he'd come in and stuff.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:32.000
He was probably in, had an instinct for being on a one-to-one or one-to-small group of people in terms of getting folks involved and doing stuff is credible.

00:30:32.000 --> 00:30:40.000
I mean, there are people that stand out, Stokely, Carmichael, and Kwame Torreina.

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:45.000
How did, how did he stand out? He was good. He certainly was a good organizer.

00:30:45.000 --> 00:30:56.000
He certainly was fearless. But I think that people really, some reason you, I, and I don't know maybe is what Ivan Ho looked like.

00:30:56.000 --> 00:31:03.000
He looked like just somebody from the field. I mean, he really did. If you looked at him, you wouldn't think he was anybody but another field hand.

00:31:03.000 --> 00:31:14.000
And he knew how to talk and act in a way that it convinced people. And then there were people like Bob Moses, who probably to me was the intellectual,

00:31:14.000 --> 00:31:25.000
who lead and snick. And I mean, he had the book learning, he had the, you know, of course the intelligence and the insight.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:40.000
And in terms of pan-Africanism and linking that, he probably eyesight as the person who, he's thinking formulated it.

00:31:40.000 --> 00:31:49.000
Yeah. So do you remember, so you're doing voter registration work and you're working with the Mississippi Farm Labor Union.

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:55.000
Do you remember the discussions in Mississippi about whether or not to put on the summer project?

00:31:55.000 --> 00:32:05.000
That happened. The summer project came right after I got there. It came about four or five months. And they were just coming as all I knew.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:19.000
So that was already in the works. It was in the works. And I was just, you know, I was now I joined in. I mean, I'm a seasoned political hack or whatever you call it.

00:32:19.000 --> 00:32:34.000
Then I would attend meetings, but I, I was naive little kid. I mean, I wasn't a little kid, but I was, you know, I was certainly, I didn't participate.

00:32:34.000 --> 00:32:39.000
Oh, wait, I might get into a discussion about whether we should go to this thing or have a rally at this church.

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:53.000
But in terms of the grand strategy, that was done over my head. And I probably, well, it was a good thing because I didn't know enough to understand what was going on.

00:32:53.000 --> 00:33:08.000
And a lot of decisions were made. And by the way, I, I told people since then, I was telling people at the 50th anniversary reunion of SNCC that the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party and the challenge

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:32.000
probably is the reason that we have a solid Republican Salad somehow. Because once and the civil, you know, once we got the Voting Rights Act and they realized that black folks were going to vote and the Democratic Party was going to probably be majority black all over the South. People fled the Republican Party. And back then, no Republican could win anything in the South.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:51.000
And so did we foresee that? I don't know that anybody at any time said, well, what the result of this is going to be is the Republican South. And that's what we have now. And that's, of course, a key political factor in a lot of the things that I think are wrong with this country.

00:33:51.000 --> 00:34:03.000
So, you know, unintended consequences. Do you have a sense of how did the, do you remember whether or how the summer project changed the work you were doing on a day-to-day basis?

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:15.000
We had a lot of volunteers who were green and didn't know what they were doing. They were willing to go out and do stuff because they didn't know how dangerous it was.

00:34:15.000 --> 00:34:27.000
We had, I didn't work with that many of them, but a lot of, there were a lot of mass demonstrations. They could knock on a lot more doors and we did that.

00:34:28.000 --> 00:34:43.000
And I guess I had a season enough to give them a lot of information. There was a lot of pushback about some of the more seasoned civil rights workers that these folks didn't know exactly what they were doing.

00:34:43.000 --> 00:34:58.000
And maybe it wasn't worth the effort because they were taking up resources. They were very useful in helping us, every call getting some of the head start schools going because a lot of them were college students with, you know, education, et cetera.

00:34:59.000 --> 00:35:11.000
I guess I was a college student of education, but I didn't think of it that way. What do you do with physics to create? You mean, right? I didn't finish it ever. But that's, you know, I was, you know, I could teach math and I did. I too didn't math sometimes.

00:35:11.000 --> 00:35:33.000
Yeah. But they were really helpful in the head start schools and some of the other programs we had people would send clothes down and we had distribution programs. And they were going to working that stuff out in terms of going out and going to field and getting someone who was chopping cotton to, to agree to join the union.

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:43.000
It takes, being a community organizer takes getting empathy from the person you're organizing. And it's a one on one or one on a few people.

00:35:43.000 --> 00:35:48.000
They didn't, they might have made it if they had lots of time, but they're only there for most of them for the summer.

00:35:48.000 --> 00:35:49.000
Yeah.

00:35:49.000 --> 00:36:02.000
I know at a certain point, Nick shifted from regular voter registration in the summer to registering people for the FTP.

00:36:02.000 --> 00:36:06.000
Were you involved in that or any of the FDP organizing?

00:36:06.000 --> 00:36:16.000
Oh, it was all one group. I mean, we didn't, that FTP weren't separate. And Lawrence Guyot was always there and people like that.

00:36:16.000 --> 00:36:23.000
Yeah. I think of it as that biggest shift.

00:36:23.000 --> 00:36:32.000
We had to get them registered. Otherwise, that was always key is getting people registered to vote because if you didn't vote, being in it.

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:41.000
But a lot of our meetings focused on joining MFDP. And so there was a lot of emphasis on that and what that could do.

00:36:41.000 --> 00:36:44.000
Where were you based that summer? Do you remember? Were you still in Cleveland?

00:36:44.000 --> 00:36:49.000
Yeah, I was, I, I was pretty much always, that's where I most of my stuff stayed.

00:36:49.000 --> 00:36:55.000
Yeah. I would go plus stay places. I went down to Delta Pines Plantation and hit out there while we were doing it.

00:36:55.000 --> 00:37:00.000
And hit out as a word because they were looking for us. And we'd sleep in ditches and stuff.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:11.000
So I have go places and maybe go work someplace for three days a week or even longer. But my stuff, which is considered a couple of pairs of jeans.

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:17.000
And I used to shave then and had a razor, I guess. That would stay in a toothbrush.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:23.000
I don't know if I took my toothbrush. No, if I brushed my teeth. I'm a must've.

00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:33.000
I know. And I must've brushed my teeth anyway. But I don't remember brushing my teeth. You never ever think about those things.

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:36.000
Routine. Routine. Those things that you do.

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:49.000
And I was, I guess I have to admit. One of the places I did a lot of organizing, especially young men and women, is I would go to the joints, drink beer and dance.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:55.000
And most of the SNCC workers didn't do a lot of that. So you developed a special talent?

00:37:55.000 --> 00:38:00.000
Yes. I drink a lot of beer. Colt 45. Yes, I drink a lot of beer.

00:38:00.000 --> 00:38:07.000
And you know, but those places to organize, you can talk to people. Wherever you can meet people and talk to them.

00:38:07.000 --> 00:38:12.000
Did you go to the precinct meetings or district caucuses or any of that going up to that?

00:38:12.000 --> 00:38:18.000
I think I'd ever go to a district caucus meeting. I certainly went to precinct meetings.

00:38:18.000 --> 00:38:26.000
And I certainly, yeah, I remember driving because I was one of the drivers. So I would, you know, in the, in the hearse.

00:38:26.000 --> 00:38:28.000
Did we talk about that?

00:38:28.000 --> 00:38:38.000
I would drive the vehicles. And so I'm, yeah, I went to, but I would drive.

00:38:38.000 --> 00:38:44.000
I wasn't up front doing stuff. I was in the back urging people to participate and stuff like that.

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:49.000
I mean, I was not in that leadership and snicked and monison that leadership.

00:38:49.000 --> 00:39:00.000
I mean, there was them that they were there to make the decisions. If it was going to be a Mississippi Democratic party, a Freedom Democratic party, then they had to take the leadership of it.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:09.000
The whole idea of the Salilinski model, where you work yourself out of a job, you want people to lead and make the decisions.

00:39:09.000 --> 00:39:14.000
So I never tried to do that.

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:23.000
Some people have talked about what it was like to kind of see that in action during the FDP meetings leading up to the, the state convention in Jackson.

00:39:23.000 --> 00:39:26.000
And then, you know, if they were there in Atlantic City.

00:39:26.000 --> 00:39:32.000
I didn't go to either Jackson or Atlanta. I know I didn't go to Atlantic City.

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:38.000
I would came up here for the challenge to Washington D.C. I was drove a whole bunch of people up.

00:39:38.000 --> 00:39:45.000
I didn't go to either. And I'm not sure why it's.

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:52.000
Again, maybe I had no reason to go except as a driver and they didn't need a driver.

00:39:52.000 --> 00:39:57.000
I was neither. When you drove people to D.C., was that to do lobbying and preparation?

00:39:57.000 --> 00:40:04.000
No, it was a challenge. I guess you call it lobbying. We came up and we stayed at also's church, filled the basement.

00:40:04.000 --> 00:40:17.000
And we'd go every day and the Congress building and to the Democratic Party headquarters and do basic lobbying.

00:40:17.000 --> 00:40:22.000
And so was this, this was the congressional challenge in the Samer and this gray and stuff.

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:27.000
So how long were you up here for that? You know, I mean, just roughly, I'm not asking you know.

00:40:27.000 --> 00:40:28.000
I'm guessing two weeks.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:32.000
Yeah, okay. And so you were helping drive people around.

00:40:32.000 --> 00:40:39.000
I would drive people. You like stories? My favorite story was, and I mean, I driven in the big city in California.

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:43.000
I driven in L.A. and San Francisco, you know, and Oakland and places like that.

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:50.000
But I was driving this car and going back to all souls from something we were at.

00:40:50.000 --> 00:40:53.000
Maybe it was a rally on the mall, I don't remember.

00:40:53.000 --> 00:41:01.000
And whoever heard of turning a six lane street into one way when it was two way the other time.

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:06.000
If D.C. has these streets and anybody who's in DC knows this.

00:41:06.000 --> 00:41:10.000
And I turned on to this street and I knew how to get back to the church.

00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:13.000
And I'm looking at all this traffic facing me.

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:17.000
And there's a cop sitting there.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:22.000
And he looks at me and then he looks at the people in the car half of which was still wearing bandanas from working in the field.

00:41:22.000 --> 00:41:28.000
Because these are mostly union people. So they were field workers and nobody told them to dress up.

00:41:28.000 --> 00:41:33.000
They didn't bring their Sunday clothes. He looks at me. He looks at the people in the car. He looks at the Mississippi tags.

00:41:33.000 --> 00:41:37.000
He looks at me and he looks at people in the car and looks at the Mississippi tags. And he just shakes his head.

00:41:38.000 --> 00:41:44.000
And he holds up all this traffic. Makes a big deal out of me. He said, come on.

00:41:44.000 --> 00:41:51.000
You know, you feel about this big. I'm saying, I'm driven in the city before but nobody has one way streets that were two way.

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:55.000
Yes, you know, and they make it one way going out because it's all about the suburbs.

00:41:55.000 --> 00:42:01.000
So it's a two way street most of the day and it's one way going out in the afternoon, one way coming in in the morning.

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:04.000
I do not drive.

00:42:08.000 --> 00:42:19.000
Did you have a chance to see Mrs. Hamer and Mrs. Gray and Mrs. Devine do their sort of speak to people or talk about the issues.

00:42:19.000 --> 00:42:24.000
I mean, that was normal because they did it all the time.

00:42:24.000 --> 00:42:37.000
Yeah, I mean, the same thing happened in DC. On one hand, as I said, I was politically more politically naive.

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:46.000
On one hand, I know this was a big deal and we were trying to upset the system and I knew all the politics of it.

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:55.000
But I didn't have a good geopolitical, I mean, I wasn't in strategy groups.

00:42:55.000 --> 00:43:05.000
And so I don't think I really was focused on the import because it was my job to get people to come.

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:09.000
Many bodies as I couldn't say. I was out there saying all this great stuff I'm going to do this, how important it is.

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:16.000
And then once we're here logistically making sure people got fed, people showed up where we're supposed to be, what building it is,

00:43:16.000 --> 00:43:19.000
give me a map so I can find it.

00:43:22.000 --> 00:43:30.000
But I wasn't at that level of leadership. Now, in the union, I had more to say and what we're trying to do with the union.

00:43:30.000 --> 00:43:42.000
But MFDP had its own leadership and they wanted local people and local officials to do it.

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:50.000
It wasn't, you know, it was, SNCC was very much about that. We were witnesses and facilitators. And that was what we're supposed to do.

00:43:50.000 --> 00:43:56.000
And what about, you mentioned GeoTroll or in reference to FDP?

00:43:56.000 --> 00:44:06.000
Well, he's a good friend and has been over the years. Sometimes I think he remembers his role as more, anyway.

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:14.000
He was key to it. He was certainly a powerful figure. And he certainly was key to developing the strategies.

00:44:14.000 --> 00:44:27.000
And being from Mississippi, he had, you know, he played that card a lot when people would say who weren't from Mississippi, we think this, he'd say, well, you're not from here, you don't get to make that decision.

00:44:27.000 --> 00:44:34.000
And I've heard him say that many, many times. He didn't take too well to people who disagreed with him.

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:50.000
I don't know if you were aware of this or involved in this at all, but I know that after the convention challenge, there was some differences between SNCC and FDP over endorsing Johnson, Humphrey and working for them. Can you speak to them?

00:44:50.000 --> 00:45:10.000
No, I really, that was, again, I let decisions like that be made by other folks. I'm, I, I, to be honest, I know what I'd say now. And I don't know what I would have said then if my opinion had been asked.

00:45:10.000 --> 00:45:18.000
But that wasn't my decision. And I shouldn't have, even if I had an opinion.

00:45:18.000 --> 00:45:28.000
But, you know, so, so, so talk about you said in the union work that you had more say in shaping things. Can you talk about that?

00:45:28.000 --> 00:45:42.000
Well, it's how we would, you know, and at one point that we even started, there was started a co-op that was union. And that wasn't Shaw, sorry, recall.

00:45:42.000 --> 00:46:00.000
But it was the strategy of what do we do now? You know, can we really have a strike? Will people, will a plantation owners just get other people in from other areas? And we did have a number of small strikes.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:18.000
Could we just leverage and demand for better wages? How many people could we get out to do certain things? And it was more day to day level about, because that was handled by a smaller group.

00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:30.000
And, like I said, there were a few leaders who were local. And so we, but we, they, we had more input.

00:46:30.000 --> 00:46:40.000
It seems like it was a real difficult context because mechanization had been, had already had such an impact on the delta and the number of laborers.

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:56.000
Yes, certainly, certainly for a lot of things. But when it came to chopping cotton and chopping cotton and explaining people don't know what to do, can you get the weeds out? Johnson grass is the biggest thing. And you take a hole and you chop all of the weeds with a hole.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:09.000
I don't know what they ever found anything that will replace just back breaking labor. And picking cotton, although there are some mechanical devices picking cotton, especially if it's a smaller plantation, it doesn't pay to do any of that by hand.

00:47:09.000 --> 00:47:20.000
So we did have some leverage. Some of the other things like corn and stuff like that, we didn't invite that battle. Yeah, you picked that automated corn pickers, etc.

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:28.000
So can you describe the decision to actually try the strike and what happened?

00:47:28.000 --> 00:47:48.000
Well, we try some small strikes on, we strike individual plantations. And there were a couple of times we actually got better wages. And there were a couple of times more than a couple, more than about eight times.

00:47:48.000 --> 00:48:07.000
And I couldn't remember the plantation owner's names if I had to, or maybe I don't know, maybe somewhere in the recesses. But it was always an ongoing decision about whether this was going to work.

00:48:07.000 --> 00:48:15.000
Do we have enough people? Were enough folks signed up from that plantation. If you didn't have the majority, then it wasn't even worth it.

00:48:15.000 --> 00:48:25.000
Would they bring others in and therefore people would just be without a job because there's nowhere else to go. Nobody else at higher you once they heard you were striking.

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:35.000
We had food banks set up on several occasions and we'd get people to send money. And that's one of the things I did when I was in the north is I'd raise money for food and clothes.

00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:46.000
So could we sustain the people and for how long and who would take care of the kids, you know, and people had some really, really hard decision.

00:48:46.000 --> 00:48:59.000
We got, we never had a large major coordinated strike across all of a large enough area of the delta to make any differences for the county, Bolivar County.

00:48:59.000 --> 00:49:14.000
But we did increase the wages for some people which then forced other plantain plantation owners. We learned, raised their wages to be competitive so people wouldn't jump to another plantation.

00:49:14.000 --> 00:49:24.000
So we had what I would call a limited success. And we considered any, you know, 10 cents an hour, a large increase.

00:49:24.000 --> 00:49:37.000
You know, I'm not sure about the timing of this and this might have been after I was trying to look at the dates, but this might have been after you left Mississippi. But at one point there's a strike where enough people are striking that people get evicted.

00:49:37.000 --> 00:49:42.000
And they set up a tent city and take over the air base. Where you part of that.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:46.000
But that was, where was that? That wasn't in Baltimore County.

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:56.000
It was Miss Blackwell. You need a Blackwell was involved. And so I know she was in Myersville, but I'm not sure, Sharky area, but I'm not sure that's where the strike was.

00:49:57.000 --> 00:50:05.000
Yeah. And I heard about actually a lot of that happened and it was still happening when I came back when I was north one time.

00:50:05.000 --> 00:50:08.000
Everything.

00:50:08.000 --> 00:50:15.000
Some of them get mixed up in my head. I'm sorry. It's been a lot of years and I don't focus on this much.

00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:24.000
I think that happened actually. It wasn't in, it wasn't in Baltimore County. Maybe I think it was in sunflower.

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:34.000
And it was set up by the time I got back, but they had a lot of internal problems.

00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:41.000
And I never really got that involved. And then it was still ongoing when I left though.

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:50.000
Okay. When you would go north and raise money, would you set up those trips or would SNCC set them up and then you'd just come in and sneak?

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:59.000
Snick would have a schedule for me. And I went to California a couple of times New York Boston, Washington D.C.

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:11.000
And they had churches. They had placed for me to stay. They just needed my body there. And I tell them what was happening and tell them how much we needed and what we needed.

00:51:11.000 --> 00:51:20.000
And then there was always some other folks from the local SNCC offices. The local SNCC offices in the north really did mostly support organizations.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:26.000
And so they would take checks and they would collect the food and that sort of thing.

00:51:26.000 --> 00:51:36.000
Yeah. So I've heard these stories about SNCC meetings, you know, when the group would gather for what, you know, sort of as a staff.

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:39.000
Did you participate in those meetings? Do you have many?

00:51:39.000 --> 00:51:50.000
We had some small ones. Of course, the Delta is in the in the west of Mississippi. Most of them were in Alabama.

00:51:50.000 --> 00:51:57.000
I mean, that's where the big, you know, in Jackson. And then the thing in Jackson. I went to a few in Jackson.

00:51:57.000 --> 00:52:01.000
But we didn't have many local. I didn't leave the area much. So you do.

00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:06.000
Yeah, I went to Jackson occasionally. I was a decent ride to go to Jackson. Yeah. Yeah.

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:13.000
So there'd be local meetings and that's where I'd attend. But I didn't go.

00:52:13.000 --> 00:52:17.000
Nor was I interested because I thought, you know, I was supposed to be working there.

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:21.000
So you'd stay close to the field when you really travel to Atlanta or different places?

00:52:21.000 --> 00:52:26.000
That's what I thought. That's what my, my role was.

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:32.000
Now I'm older and different and I get involved in leadership decisions and stuff like that.

00:52:32.000 --> 00:52:38.000
But even then, even now, if you, I'd work a lot of political campaigns and,

00:52:38.000 --> 00:52:46.000
and there are, when you do a political campaign, I may, for quasi-infumé, I was the, his coordinator from Montgomery County.

00:52:46.000 --> 00:52:51.000
And so Montgomery County decisions, you know, I was part of all those decisions.

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:57.000
Statewide, you know, I went to not that many of the meetings and because they didn't have that many statewide.

00:52:57.000 --> 00:53:02.000
And then there was a core of people that made decisions and that's, that's a top-downs thing again.

00:53:02.000 --> 00:53:12.000
But that's a lot of ways things happen. They made decisions that, that, and we got a newsletter that we tell us about.

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:15.000
What was that called?

00:53:15.000 --> 00:53:17.000
Hmm. Was that a Mississippi newsletter?

00:53:17.000 --> 00:53:19.000
No, it was a, it was a, it was a New York newsletter.

00:53:19.000 --> 00:53:21.000
Was that the one for staff?

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:24.000
Yeah, and we get that.

00:53:24.000 --> 00:53:31.000
And then of course we get phone calls and they tell us, and we go watch line, you know, you know, you're about to watch line, we go watch line.

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:40.000
And, and then, and the newsletter was always great because, was it Frank Chachorca?

00:53:40.000 --> 00:53:43.000
It was a great, great, hard stuff. Yeah.

00:53:43.000 --> 00:53:45.000
Really, I wonder what happened to him?

00:53:45.000 --> 00:53:51.000
I think he passed not that long ago, like in the last four years maybe.

00:53:51.000 --> 00:53:58.000
I remember, I never did. You know, I, I'm on a SNCC email list and I can't read it all. I'm sorry.

00:53:58.000 --> 00:54:04.000
It's, you know, that there's got to be 30 emails a week and I, you know, I'm in a lot of email lists.

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:09.000
Yeah, but Lee Bank had, I heard, had passed, I heard that when I was at the reunion.

00:54:09.000 --> 00:54:11.000
Okay. I believe that's correct.

00:54:11.000 --> 00:54:13.000
I don't know much about him.

00:54:13.000 --> 00:54:16.000
No, Lee is a woman. Oh, okay. I didn't know much about her.

00:54:16.000 --> 00:54:22.000
She was, she was, she was, I guess, director of the Mississippi Freedom Library Union.

00:54:22.000 --> 00:54:26.000
Okay. Do you, can you tell us about her?

00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:42.000
Strong woman, very thoughtful, well organized, knew everybody, didn't do a lot of, in the field organizing herself, but she, you know, she was,

00:54:42.000 --> 00:54:47.000
the person who, you know, all decisions went through her for the union.

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:49.000
Where was she from?

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:50.000
I believe Cleveland.

00:54:50.000 --> 00:54:53.000
Yeah.

00:54:53.000 --> 00:54:56.000
I believe Cleveland.

00:54:56.000 --> 00:55:00.000
If it wasn't Cleveland, there was somewhere around there because that roots were in that area.

00:55:00.000 --> 00:55:03.000
So from the Delta, for sure. Yeah.

00:55:03.000 --> 00:55:13.000
So the, the, the, the, the SNCC staff meeting in Waveland, Mississippi in November of 64 is one of these sort of infamous meetings.

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:15.000
Do you have any recollection of that?

00:55:15.000 --> 00:55:17.000
Is that the kind of thing that you wouldn't go to?

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:18.000
I didn't go to.

00:55:18.000 --> 00:55:19.000
You just stay in the field.

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:21.000
I probably read, read about it.

00:55:21.000 --> 00:55:22.000
Yeah.

00:55:22.000 --> 00:55:24.000
That doesn't even ring any bail of bells.

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:44.000
I mean, there was a lot of sort of discussion in the organization about the white volunteers who were staying on and, and a contingent had gone to Guinea through Harry Belafonte, and there was a lot of sort of flux within the organization about what do we do now in the aftermath of the challenge?

00:55:44.000 --> 00:55:47.000
And form an invited people to write position papers.

00:55:47.000 --> 00:55:53.000
And so there was this, you know, a lot of several days in Waveland, Mississippi discussing all of these.

00:55:53.000 --> 00:55:58.000
Yeah. I remember hearing that.

00:55:58.000 --> 00:56:09.000
As I told you, there was some resentment about some of the volunteers who, who were not steeped in the SNCC tradition of, you know, its local control.

00:56:09.000 --> 00:56:17.000
And they would come into meetings and sometimes want to make decisions and they'd stand up in meetings and say, well, we think this and that.

00:56:17.000 --> 00:56:20.000
And I tell them afterwards, it's not our business.

00:56:20.000 --> 00:56:26.000
You know, unless you're from here, you don't make a decision about here.

00:56:26.000 --> 00:56:28.000
So yeah, there was some pushback.

00:56:28.000 --> 00:56:30.000
And that was discussed in that meeting.

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:33.000
I heard about that.

00:56:33.000 --> 00:56:38.000
I didn't get to send. Nobody was asked to leave that I know of.

00:56:38.000 --> 00:56:45.000
I mean, so I don't know that any hard decisions that I knew of came out.

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:48.000
And to be honest, I haven't read a lot of the books.

00:56:48.000 --> 00:56:56.000
I know Gene Wiley, who I've mentioned to you, who's a dear friend, and worked on a number of the history projects.

00:56:56.000 --> 00:56:59.000
And you know, whenever I'm in California, I stay at her house and she's dead.

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:01.000
We don't have to show her those days much enough.

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:04.000
To be honest, I haven't read any of the stuff she's written, really.

00:57:04.000 --> 00:57:06.000
I moved on.

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:09.000
Did you know her from SNCC?

00:57:09.000 --> 00:57:12.000
I met her, I think, one time.

00:57:12.000 --> 00:57:15.000
No, twice. She didn't come out in the field much.

00:57:15.000 --> 00:57:23.000
I'm not going to other things she doesn't believe in using outhouses and every, no place I ever worked at anything but outhouses.

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:26.000
And she liked, you know, she was an office person.

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:34.000
She, again, tremendously organized, thoughtful, and analytical.

00:57:34.000 --> 00:57:40.000
And she's like Moses, like Bob Moses.

00:57:40.000 --> 00:57:43.000
So you said that there's tons and tons of stories.

00:57:43.000 --> 00:57:45.000
Can you tell us some of your favorite ones?

00:57:45.000 --> 00:57:47.000
Favorite ones.

00:57:47.000 --> 00:57:50.000
I can talk about it in public.

00:57:50.000 --> 00:57:56.000
Well, one time the Deacons of Defense and Justice came.

00:57:56.000 --> 00:58:04.000
And I guess you know who it is, but they were a group from Louisiana and they decided they would have come across the border.

00:58:04.000 --> 00:58:08.000
And we had, they energized a lot of people.

00:58:08.000 --> 00:58:13.000
And of course, Nick was non-violent, so we know I couldn't, whatever.

00:58:13.000 --> 00:58:18.000
But we had this deputy sheriff, deputy weeks, I think, was his name.

00:58:18.000 --> 00:58:20.000
I don't know his first name.

00:58:20.000 --> 00:58:22.000
Who used to beat folks all the time.

00:58:22.000 --> 00:58:24.000
And he was just pretty open about it.

00:58:24.000 --> 00:58:27.000
And he stuck his shotgun in my chest one time.

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:30.000
And he was not exactly a friendly guy.

00:58:30.000 --> 00:58:38.000
Somebody apparently threw him all the time cocktail on his plant porch in this place in the country where he and his family stayed.

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:40.000
And nobody was hurt.

00:58:40.000 --> 00:58:43.000
He changed around 100%.

00:58:43.000 --> 00:58:46.000
Or 90% or 75%.

00:58:46.000 --> 00:58:49.000
And he had a lot of people attitude to being a nasty son of a bitch.

00:58:49.000 --> 00:58:51.000
Do you have an explanation for that?

00:58:51.000 --> 00:58:53.000
He didn't want to see his kids burnt up.

00:58:53.000 --> 00:58:58.000
So he figured that he had to do right if you aren't going to see that kind of retaliation?

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:00.000
I know if he could hold it right.

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:03.000
He had to pull back because people could fight back.

00:59:03.000 --> 00:59:11.000
And as I said, you know, Nick was non-violent and officially I don't know anything about any of that.

00:59:12.000 --> 00:59:13.000
To him.

00:59:13.000 --> 00:59:16.000
You know, even though I was considered one of the drivers around there.

00:59:16.000 --> 00:59:18.000
Oh, another good story.

00:59:18.000 --> 00:59:22.000
I was the one, because you know, we get chased a lot down country roads.

00:59:22.000 --> 00:59:31.000
And what I would rig up all the, not all the SNCC cars, and numerous SNCC cars is I would run a wire to the tail lights and put a switch under the dashboard.

00:59:31.000 --> 00:59:35.000
So if you were driving at night and you were being followed, you could turn off your tail lights.

00:59:35.000 --> 00:59:37.000
That's Andy.

00:59:37.000 --> 00:59:41.000
You know, there was little things you did you didn't learn to do so I could.

00:59:41.000 --> 00:59:43.000
Because I'd worked on cars when I was young.

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:46.000
Do you remember the impetus for the Deacons coming to town?

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:53.000
I don't know that, well, they wanted to help.

00:59:53.000 --> 01:00:02.000
And they believed that fighting back was a solution, which was not a SNCC authorized solution.

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:07.000
And they had, but the meetings were held right where I lived.

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:10.000
So it was a little hard not to be part of it.

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:13.000
And was that the Meredith March?

01:00:13.000 --> 01:00:18.000
When they were, the Meredith March was in June 66 from Memphis to Jackson.

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:23.000
And I know the Deacons were protection for that March.

01:00:23.000 --> 01:00:31.000
No, it was a group of about six guys, five or six guys.

01:00:31.000 --> 01:00:38.000
Very easily guys who wouldn't want to push the wrong way.

01:00:38.000 --> 01:00:40.000
And they just came and talked to local folks.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:44.000
And we had half dozen meetings with people coming to talk to them.

01:00:44.000 --> 01:00:49.000
And, you know, I'm not sure they, I didn't host to me.

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:54.000
I mean, SNCC can't do that, but, you know, stuff happens.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:01:00.000
Well, I mean, I know that there was, I know quite a bit of discussion and quite a bit of non-discussion

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:07.000
about the issue of non-violence and what it meant for SNCC people and how that shifted over time.

01:01:07.000 --> 01:01:12.000
Yeah, well, I think everyone, and I was part of a number of those discussions,

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:22.000
everyone agreed that we would be non-violent, but whether it was a tactic or we believed in it morally,

01:01:22.000 --> 01:01:25.000
there was some real difference of opinion.

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:32.000
And as far as I know, it was simply agreed up until the time I left.

01:01:32.000 --> 01:01:39.000
And of course, things started to change and started more afrocentric concerns.

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:46.000
That, you know, why you did it wasn't important as long as you were officially non-violent.

01:01:46.000 --> 01:01:48.000
Yeah.

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:52.000
And then with those two schools of thought.

01:01:52.000 --> 01:01:55.000
But was there a conversation?

01:01:55.000 --> 01:01:58.000
Were you part of any conversation with local people about that?

01:01:58.000 --> 01:01:59.000
Oh, sure.

01:01:59.000 --> 01:02:03.000
Yeah, I was part of, you know, people would say, we ought to just go get our guns.

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:07.000
And I'd say, well, in general, I don't think that's going to work.

01:02:07.000 --> 01:02:10.000
Because it wouldn't have.

01:02:10.000 --> 01:02:17.000
And we didn't have any manipulation of the levers of power.

01:02:17.000 --> 01:02:22.000
So any armaments that people had were small hunting rifles or shotguns.

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:27.000
The one incident I was telling you about with Deputy Weeks was very isolated.

01:02:27.000 --> 01:02:29.000
He was out there by himself.

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:32.000
And so there was nobody around to watch his house.

01:02:32.000 --> 01:02:34.000
And that one incident.

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:36.000
And he was really a son of a bitch.

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:43.000
I mean, he was, he would do things that most of the police force would never do.

01:02:43.000 --> 01:02:48.000
So he probably didn't have a lot of backing either because it looked bad.

01:02:48.000 --> 01:02:51.000
What kind of things did he do?

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:56.000
He'd just walk up and smack people and just walk down the street if he thought they weren't, you know,

01:02:56.000 --> 01:02:59.000
he'd, you know, walk up to young people and even old people.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:02.000
And push them and slap them around.

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:07.000
I'm just with no provocation whatsoever.

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:11.000
You know, there were cameras on when he put a shotgun and was a demonstration.

01:03:11.000 --> 01:03:14.000
We were about photo rights and he put a shotgun in my chest.

01:03:14.000 --> 01:03:19.000
And that was caught on tape somewhere and he got some feedback about that.

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:21.000
And he's a ball of her county deputy?

01:03:21.000 --> 01:03:22.000
Yeah.

01:03:22.000 --> 01:03:24.000
Cleveland.

01:03:24.000 --> 01:03:26.000
Maybe Cleveland City.

01:03:26.000 --> 01:03:28.000
Also like a city police officer?

01:03:28.000 --> 01:03:32.000
City police officer.

01:03:32.000 --> 01:03:36.000
I don't think I understood which, we once stopped and we had to start it.

01:03:36.000 --> 01:03:38.000
Maybe they were all county.

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:42.000
Generally in Mississippi, there were city police and county sheriff and deputies.

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:45.000
So he would have been county because he was a deputy.

01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:46.000
Yeah, you're right.

01:03:46.000 --> 01:03:47.000
You're right.

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:48.000
He must have been county.

01:03:48.000 --> 01:03:51.000
Though at a certain point Mississippi started having all these auxiliary police.

01:03:51.000 --> 01:03:54.000
And a lot of times they were the ones that were most out of control.

01:03:54.000 --> 01:03:56.000
He'd been known, people knew him for years.

01:03:56.000 --> 01:04:02.000
So I think, yeah, he was, he was, he was, he was, had been there for a while.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:05.000
I mean, he was, people talked about him from the first day I got there.

01:04:05.000 --> 01:04:06.000
Yeah.

01:04:06.000 --> 01:04:12.000
But he was, he was, you know, one of the biggest problems.

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:15.000
Do you remember the Meredith March?

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:22.000
This is the March where, which is most infamous for Carmichael, introducing the phrase black

01:04:22.000 --> 01:04:24.000
power to a national audience, really.

01:04:24.000 --> 01:04:30.000
In Greenwood, he uses the phrase black power to capture June 66.

01:04:30.000 --> 01:04:32.000
No, I don't.

01:04:32.000 --> 01:04:34.000
It's a matter of fact.

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:39.000
And it's interesting, like I said, we didn't get news.

01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:43.000
So with it made national headlines, I didn't find out about, went to the North.

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:44.000
Yeah.

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:48.000
Well, it's interesting because James Meredith starts this isolated March.

01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:49.000
Yeah.

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:50.000
He's going to go by himself.

01:04:50.000 --> 01:04:52.000
He called it the March against fear and then he shot second day out.

01:04:52.000 --> 01:04:53.000
Yeah.

01:04:53.000 --> 01:04:58.000
And so then civil rights organizations go to matches to pick this up.

01:04:58.000 --> 01:05:03.000
But SNCC made it a kind of, um, organized, a voter registration organizing campaign.

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:06.000
Because this is after the passage of the Voting Rights Act.

01:05:06.000 --> 01:05:15.000
And so they tried to, everywhere they went, tap into their SNCC, um, contacts and networks and use it to register voters.

01:05:15.000 --> 01:05:20.000
So that's why I thought it might have been not just through the national news, but through the...

01:05:20.000 --> 01:05:26.000
Uh, it, it, if I was involved, I, I don't remember it.

01:05:26.000 --> 01:05:32.000
The biggest demonstration, we didn't do many big things, was when we went down to Jackson,

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:40.000
and I don't know what year that was, maybe 64 or 60, yeah, maybe 64.

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:42.000
And they arrested everybody.

01:05:42.000 --> 01:05:44.000
At the fair and took them to the fairgrounds?

01:05:44.000 --> 01:05:45.000
Yeah, I was in the fairgrounds.

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:46.000
I think that was 65.

01:05:46.000 --> 01:05:47.000
65?

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:52.000
That was the, the biggest event in Mississippi I was at.

01:05:52.000 --> 01:05:53.000
I think it tells us.

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:55.000
And we were, you know, they locked us in the fairgrounds.

01:05:55.000 --> 01:05:59.000
They had some sort of, I guess I remember being two petitions occasion.

01:05:59.000 --> 01:06:00.000
You see the door open.

01:06:00.000 --> 01:06:02.000
We could see that the women were locked in another one.

01:06:02.000 --> 01:06:06.000
All the men were locked in, in our side.

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:11.000
And I started out in solitary confinement, then they let me out into the general population.

01:06:11.000 --> 01:06:15.000
Were you in solitary because you identified as one of the organizers?

01:06:15.000 --> 01:06:16.000
I believe so, yeah.

01:06:17.000 --> 01:06:20.000
Because I brought up being grouped down.

01:06:20.000 --> 01:06:23.000
And then I don't know why they let me out.

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:24.000
You mean you never knew anything.

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:28.000
Funny story about that.

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:34.000
And they, a lot of times they had the door open so you could see was a big double door.

01:06:34.000 --> 01:06:35.000
You could see the women.

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:39.000
And of course, a bunch of guys, I wasn't watching the guys, I was watching the women.

01:06:39.000 --> 01:06:45.000
You know, and this cop was trying to get this woman to move big women.

01:06:45.000 --> 01:06:51.000
And she was sitting down and he hit her one time with his billy club.

01:06:51.000 --> 01:06:53.000
And she just covered her head.

01:06:53.000 --> 01:06:56.000
And then he went to pick her up and he had, she must have weighed 250 pounds.

01:06:56.000 --> 01:07:00.000
He had her halfway up and she need him in the groin.

01:07:00.000 --> 01:07:03.000
And you could hear him scream all the way through the walls.

01:07:03.000 --> 01:07:07.000
I'm sure then they shut the door and I'm sure they beat the shit out of her.

01:07:07.000 --> 01:07:08.000
But you know.

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:24.000
I've interviewed a few men who have said that one of the things that they found most difficult about nonviolence was not protecting, not moving to defend women and children.

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:25.000
Yes.

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:28.000
And given their upbringing and their socialization.

01:07:28.000 --> 01:07:35.000
Was that an issue for you?

01:07:35.000 --> 01:07:48.000
Well, more than a few times when we had demonstrations, you know, and then we'd have demonstrations where we'd go to various times.

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:56.000
They'd start swinging the clubs at everybody and I would just get, I mean, I guess I knew there was nothing we could do.

01:07:56.000 --> 01:08:04.000
I would just lay over people and protect them, let them hit me.

01:08:04.000 --> 01:08:13.000
Even though I thought when I was younger, I guess you didn't occur to me that that was an option.

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:24.000
Because I think if you'd really thought back, unless you did something, you know, plan, some sort of plan counter attack, you just get beaten up and thrown in jail.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:34.000
And as it was, I actually saw my arrest record one time many years later and it was about this thick.

01:08:34.000 --> 01:08:38.000
The worst jail I was in, I don't know why I was in that jail.

01:08:38.000 --> 01:08:42.000
Worst jail I was in, I don't even remember where it was.

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:47.000
But they would put us, you know, there was white cells, of course, in the blacks.

01:08:47.000 --> 01:08:50.000
The black cell was one cell, one big cell.

01:08:50.000 --> 01:08:54.000
It had a sink and a toilet and mattresses and it all sloped.

01:08:54.000 --> 01:09:01.000
It was a slope so there was a drain in the center and the toilet was overflowing and the mattresses were near the center.

01:09:01.000 --> 01:09:04.000
So basically they were soaked in urine and feces.

01:09:04.000 --> 01:09:07.000
And so you slept on the floor uphill.

01:09:07.000 --> 01:09:10.000
That wasn't a nice place, I recall.

01:09:10.000 --> 01:09:13.000
That was probably the worst jail I was in.

01:09:13.000 --> 01:09:15.000
Yeah, much more in a few jails.

01:09:15.000 --> 01:09:20.000
Sometimes if there were more of us, we'd do things, you know, like, I remember I used, because I carve and stuff.

01:09:20.000 --> 01:09:26.000
And I remember making, taking a Styrofoam cups and making a chest set.

01:09:26.000 --> 01:09:34.000
Because we could smoke and we'd get cigarettes and I melted a chest set and we had, on the bars and we had this vertical chest set.

01:09:34.000 --> 01:09:35.000
Yeah.

01:09:35.000 --> 01:09:38.000
And you'd make a chest.

01:09:38.000 --> 01:09:44.000
And I was really putting effort into getting these beautiful chest pieces, the ponds, the queen.

01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:46.000
You know, you know, what you're going to do when you're in jail.

01:09:46.000 --> 01:09:48.000
Yeah, plenty of time to work at it, right?

01:09:48.000 --> 01:09:49.000
Yeah.

01:09:49.000 --> 01:09:50.000
Yeah.

01:09:50.000 --> 01:09:51.000
Yeah, I don't remember.

01:09:51.000 --> 01:09:53.000
You just went to jail, it was something that happened, you know.

01:09:53.000 --> 01:09:56.000
You know, you talked about, you had no idea about Mississippi, you know.

01:09:56.000 --> 01:10:01.000
So what was it like to then spend, you know, four years there?

01:10:01.000 --> 01:10:07.000
I mean, how did you adapt or what did Mississippi mean to you after you'd been there a while?

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:13.000
I was working, I mean, I believed in changing the system.

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:20.000
And it was an effort to do that.

01:10:20.000 --> 01:10:35.000
In retrospect, I wish I had more insight into what I was, you know, some of the decisions I made and what the effect would be, long term and short term for the people I was working for.

01:10:35.000 --> 01:10:50.000
But I accepted the role of being a minion, I guess, and knowing I was doing something I believed in.

01:10:50.000 --> 01:10:55.000
I thought it was part of what life's about, I don't know.

01:10:55.000 --> 01:10:57.000
It really wasn't very philosophical about it.

01:10:57.000 --> 01:11:00.000
It was something you did, and you had to do.

01:11:00.000 --> 01:11:09.000
And often when I was in California, I would, you know, go work with C-Farm workers again and talk to them and give them, tell them some things we were doing and we share information.

01:11:09.000 --> 01:11:12.000
I know by the lights.

01:11:12.000 --> 01:11:13.000
You want to put them on?

01:11:13.000 --> 01:11:15.000
Well, no.

01:11:15.000 --> 01:11:18.000
I'll tell you if it's...

01:11:18.000 --> 01:11:22.000
Okay. I can't see anybody, you know.

01:11:22.000 --> 01:11:25.000
Well, there's a world out here.

01:11:25.000 --> 01:11:32.000
I'm getting hits on them. I think it would be really difficult for people.

01:11:32.000 --> 01:11:33.000
All right.

01:11:33.000 --> 01:11:35.000
I'll be in a blurred world.

01:11:35.000 --> 01:11:38.000
I'll get the lights up and higher.

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:39.000
It's okay.

01:11:39.000 --> 01:11:42.000
Next break, I'll get some more to drink too.

01:11:42.000 --> 01:11:43.000
Do you want to do that now?

01:11:43.000 --> 01:11:44.000
No, it's okay.

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:55.000
I think by the late 60s, SNCC has people working with the Farm Labor Union, not the Farm Labor, but the Farm Workers in California as well.

01:11:55.000 --> 01:11:58.000
Right. Do you know anything about that?

01:11:58.000 --> 01:12:02.000
Is there actually a couple of SNCC people out in California?

01:12:02.000 --> 01:12:04.000
Well, we're on SNCC staff.

01:12:04.000 --> 01:12:05.000
Yeah.

01:12:05.000 --> 01:12:07.000
And were they...no, I don't.

01:12:07.000 --> 01:12:08.000
Okay.

01:12:08.000 --> 01:12:14.000
It's interesting that since the reunion, I have...

01:12:14.000 --> 01:12:17.000
There was a Latina who was doing...

01:12:17.000 --> 01:12:22.000
She was doing some, you know, Latinos from Latinas who were involved in SNCC.

01:12:22.000 --> 01:12:25.000
There weren't many of us, and I didn't know any at the time.

01:12:25.000 --> 01:12:28.000
But I've now found some others.

01:12:28.000 --> 01:12:34.000
But do you know if they were black, white, or Anglo, or...?

01:12:34.000 --> 01:12:41.000
I think that they were black and white.

01:12:41.000 --> 01:12:42.000
But I wouldn't...

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:45.000
But I don't know a lot of detail, so I don't want to...

01:12:45.000 --> 01:12:48.000
And a number of her elements and connections.

01:12:48.000 --> 01:12:49.000
Yeah, she wasn't the one.

01:12:49.000 --> 01:12:53.000
But she's not who I'm thinking of with this particular piece.

01:12:53.000 --> 01:12:59.000
I ask, you know, to a certain extent, Farm Workers was segmented,

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:01.000
which strike they were working?

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:05.000
There was a strawberry strike, there was a tomato strike, and of course it was a grape strike,

01:13:05.000 --> 01:13:08.000
which was the one with a big boycott.

01:13:08.000 --> 01:13:11.000
And there were a lot of efforts in different areas,

01:13:11.000 --> 01:13:15.000
Delano Valley and San Joaquin Valley and stuff like that.

01:13:15.000 --> 01:13:17.000
I'm not going to be able to pull it up.

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:23.000
I've read some work on it by a historian, and so she was piecing together the interconnections.

01:13:23.000 --> 01:13:26.000
But I don't have enough detail to be able to say with any...

01:13:26.000 --> 01:13:30.000
Yeah, I don't know there was any formal interconnection,

01:13:30.000 --> 01:13:32.000
while I was involved.

01:13:32.000 --> 01:13:37.000
And when occasionally I go back, communication, we didn't have cell phones.

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:38.000
Yeah.

01:13:38.000 --> 01:13:43.000
We didn't have the internet, how things have changed so much.

01:13:43.000 --> 01:13:48.000
So getting word back was, you know, when you talk to somebody on the phone,

01:13:48.000 --> 01:13:50.000
phone calls back, then we're expensive.

01:13:50.000 --> 01:13:52.000
That's why we use the watch line.

01:13:52.000 --> 01:13:54.000
I tell kids today, you know,

01:13:54.000 --> 01:13:57.000
we used to make calls only at night,

01:13:57.000 --> 01:14:00.000
and then we made use to just make sure we talked to, you know,

01:14:00.000 --> 01:14:04.000
when somebody had it, we'd call person to person,

01:14:04.000 --> 01:14:07.000
and then after they said, no, you know, they'd get the person

01:14:07.000 --> 01:14:11.000
and so you could call then station to station,

01:14:11.000 --> 01:14:14.000
that you couldn't afford communication.

01:14:14.000 --> 01:14:18.000
And now things are so much different, you know,

01:14:18.000 --> 01:14:23.000
between unlimited phone calls and the internet, you'd know,

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:26.000
but back then, once you left a place, you were isolated.

01:14:26.000 --> 01:14:31.000
It was very difficult for me to find out what was happening in Mississippi after I left.

01:14:31.000 --> 01:14:35.000
I wanted to ask about, you know, sort of how you came to leave,

01:14:35.000 --> 01:14:42.000
but before I do, there are a couple of documents that we dug up on the Mississippi Freedom Labor Union.

01:14:42.000 --> 01:14:45.000
Okay, and for that, I've got to put on my glasses,

01:14:45.000 --> 01:14:47.000
because all this looks like this is...

01:14:47.000 --> 01:14:50.000
Oh boy!

01:14:50.000 --> 01:14:55.000
I think I did this, or so, I remember this is going...

01:14:55.000 --> 01:14:59.000
Yes, my goodness, I'd love to get a copy of this.

01:14:59.000 --> 01:15:02.000
You can keep that.

01:15:02.000 --> 01:15:05.000
I think I typed this.

01:15:05.000 --> 01:15:07.000
That's the Chorca.

01:15:07.000 --> 01:15:08.000
Yeah, I wondered.

01:15:08.000 --> 01:15:11.000
That's for me.

01:15:11.000 --> 01:15:15.000
I didn't do this one.

01:15:15.000 --> 01:15:18.000
No, because I would never put that square...

01:15:18.000 --> 01:15:21.000
I didn't know.

01:15:21.000 --> 01:15:24.000
I still have snake pins, by the way, with that little...

01:15:24.000 --> 01:15:26.000
Oh, do you?

01:15:26.000 --> 01:15:28.000
People have tried to get them.

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:30.000
No, you can't have them.

01:15:30.000 --> 01:15:33.000
I also have the Mississippi Freedom Labor Union button,

01:15:33.000 --> 01:15:34.000
which I think...

01:15:34.000 --> 01:15:35.000
Yeah, I don't know what that looks like.

01:15:35.000 --> 01:15:36.000
And show it to you.

01:15:36.000 --> 01:15:37.000
I'd love to see it.

01:15:37.000 --> 01:15:39.000
It's upstairs.

01:15:39.000 --> 01:15:41.000
It's a black and white hand,

01:15:41.000 --> 01:15:44.000
and then there's a lantern being held in front of it.

01:15:45.000 --> 01:15:47.000
Oh, my goodness.

01:15:47.000 --> 01:15:49.000
Yeah, I did this first one.

01:15:49.000 --> 01:15:50.000
So, can you...

01:15:50.000 --> 01:15:52.000
We can maybe get a picture of that

01:15:52.000 --> 01:15:55.000
so people know what you're talking about, but can you tell us about that?

01:15:55.000 --> 01:15:57.000
Okay, I'll see anything else.

01:15:57.000 --> 01:16:00.000
I'm a mere graphed, long of the spirit of the project.

01:16:00.000 --> 01:16:04.000
No, I don't remember seeing this one.

01:16:04.000 --> 01:16:06.000
Oh, my goodness.

01:16:06.000 --> 01:16:08.000
My goodness, got it.

01:16:08.000 --> 01:16:12.000
Flashback to the path for this page.

01:16:12.000 --> 01:16:14.000
City workshops.

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:16.000
I don't remember this.

01:16:16.000 --> 01:16:18.000
I'd like to read it, but of course, not going to do it right now.

01:16:18.000 --> 01:16:21.000
And this is the...

01:16:21.000 --> 01:16:25.000
You said, hold it for a second.

01:16:25.000 --> 01:16:26.000
Okay.

01:16:26.000 --> 01:16:28.000
Okay, thanks.

01:16:28.000 --> 01:16:29.000
Good.

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:32.000
So, can you tell us about how you came to type that up

01:16:32.000 --> 01:16:33.000
and who I was involved in?

01:16:33.000 --> 01:16:35.000
Because I could tie it together.

01:16:35.000 --> 01:16:37.000
I could type.

01:16:37.000 --> 01:16:40.000
And they let you in the field.

01:16:40.000 --> 01:16:42.000
What did we have?

01:16:42.000 --> 01:16:45.000
We had this little portable typewriter.

01:16:45.000 --> 01:16:48.000
It was like a royal...

01:16:48.000 --> 01:16:52.000
little, you know, the little keys, and it's smack it, and they sound terrible.

01:16:52.000 --> 01:16:55.000
And also, there were people who had the churches had typewriters.

01:16:55.000 --> 01:16:57.000
There were people with typewriters.

01:16:57.000 --> 01:17:03.000
And no such thing as a computer back then.

01:17:03.000 --> 01:17:06.000
This came out of meetings.

01:17:06.000 --> 01:17:10.000
And kind of work I do, yeah.

01:17:10.000 --> 01:17:12.000
My phone.

01:17:12.000 --> 01:17:14.000
How much I could pay, yeah.

01:17:14.000 --> 01:17:20.000
You know, we took notes and Lee ran the meeting.

01:17:20.000 --> 01:17:23.000
And I think...

01:17:23.000 --> 01:17:25.000
I don't even know which meeting this was, though.

01:17:25.000 --> 01:17:29.000
Mostly, Reverend Jackson was in most of those.

01:17:29.000 --> 01:17:31.000
Miss Ruffin would come a lot of times.

01:17:31.000 --> 01:17:33.000
Fannie Lou had lots of stuff.

01:17:33.000 --> 01:17:35.000
So she wasn't at all a lot of meetings.

01:17:35.000 --> 01:17:37.000
There was another minister who...

01:17:37.000 --> 01:17:39.000
And I don't know when we did this.

01:17:39.000 --> 01:17:43.000
I mean, this wasn't such a big deal that it...

01:17:43.000 --> 01:17:45.000
that it sticks in my memory.

01:17:45.000 --> 01:17:47.000
But I remember typing it.

01:17:47.000 --> 01:17:49.000
And I don't...

01:17:49.000 --> 01:17:50.000
How did we copy?

01:17:50.000 --> 01:17:51.000
How do we copy?

01:17:51.000 --> 01:17:52.000
We didn't have photocopies, though.

01:17:52.000 --> 01:17:56.000
We had Memeograph and we had stencils.

01:17:56.000 --> 01:17:58.000
Dict...

01:17:58.000 --> 01:17:59.000
Dictograph.

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:00.000
Dicta...

01:18:00.000 --> 01:18:01.000
Okay.

01:18:01.000 --> 01:18:02.000
Memeograph.

01:18:02.000 --> 01:18:04.000
Yeah, it was special from...

01:18:04.000 --> 01:18:06.000
But then there was a Dicta thing.

01:18:06.000 --> 01:18:07.000
I forgot.

01:18:07.000 --> 01:18:10.000
But that looks like the kind where you cut the stencil.

01:18:10.000 --> 01:18:11.000
Yeah.

01:18:11.000 --> 01:18:12.000
But they both...

01:18:12.000 --> 01:18:16.000
Memeograph is one type and there was another copying thing.

01:18:16.000 --> 01:18:19.000
Dicta something or other.

01:18:19.000 --> 01:18:22.000
Did the Atlanta print shop ever do anything for you?

01:18:22.000 --> 01:18:23.000
Not.

01:18:23.000 --> 01:18:25.000
There were no black print shops and no white print shop.

01:18:25.000 --> 01:18:27.000
But we didn't have the money to do that sort of thing.

01:18:27.000 --> 01:18:29.000
We could have asked...

01:18:29.000 --> 01:18:32.000
For some of the flyers we had sometimes,

01:18:32.000 --> 01:18:35.000
we would tell people up north that we wanted.

01:18:35.000 --> 01:18:37.000
If somebody was coming down,

01:18:37.000 --> 01:18:39.000
you'd say, can you do this and we get a...

01:18:39.000 --> 01:18:41.000
You know, I'm just copies of that way.

01:18:41.000 --> 01:18:45.000
I know the SNCC office in Atlanta at a certain point had a print shop.

01:18:45.000 --> 01:18:47.000
Yeah, they had a print shop.

01:18:47.000 --> 01:18:48.000
I know they had a copier.

01:18:48.000 --> 01:18:50.000
Now they had a print shop actually.

01:18:50.000 --> 01:18:53.000
Wilson...

01:18:53.000 --> 01:18:56.000
Brown?

01:18:56.000 --> 01:18:57.000
That's right.

01:18:57.000 --> 01:18:59.000
I know somebody who was line a type.

01:18:59.000 --> 01:19:01.000
Who used to do line a type.

01:19:01.000 --> 01:19:03.000
I remember talking to somebody who had that.

01:19:03.000 --> 01:19:04.000
And I was jealous or something.

01:19:04.000 --> 01:19:06.000
I said, you know, that's stuff.

01:19:06.000 --> 01:19:08.000
Because we didn't have any of that.

01:19:08.000 --> 01:19:12.000
I know at a certain point, Varela was making films.

01:19:12.000 --> 01:19:15.000
The people coming through doing things.

01:19:15.000 --> 01:19:19.000
A lot of the churches had...

01:19:19.000 --> 01:19:22.000
It's not Memeograph is another...

01:19:22.000 --> 01:19:24.000
And that's what I think this has done.

01:19:24.000 --> 01:19:26.000
That's why the copy is so poor.

01:19:27.000 --> 01:19:28.000
Dictigraph.

01:19:28.000 --> 01:19:30.000
Dictus something or other.

01:19:30.000 --> 01:19:33.000
Anyway, it's much easier to cut this stencil in.

01:19:33.000 --> 01:19:38.000
Memeograph, if you make a mistake, you had to cut it off with a razor blade.

01:19:38.000 --> 01:19:40.000
And this one...

01:19:40.000 --> 01:19:42.000
This was a blue paper.

01:19:42.000 --> 01:19:43.000
And you put them...

01:19:43.000 --> 01:19:45.000
Again, the master in and crank it along.

01:19:45.000 --> 01:19:47.000
Yeah.

01:19:47.000 --> 01:19:49.000
I worked...

01:19:49.000 --> 01:19:51.000
Boy, those, yeah.

01:19:51.000 --> 01:19:52.000
So it was something like that.

01:19:52.000 --> 01:19:55.000
Would you carry that around then to people and use it as a way to...

01:19:55.000 --> 01:20:01.000
No, actually, I think we would do this in churches after a speech.

01:20:01.000 --> 01:20:04.000
We'd have all the rabble rise in this singing.

01:20:04.000 --> 01:20:07.000
And people would make presentations.

01:20:07.000 --> 01:20:10.000
And we'd have either...

01:20:10.000 --> 01:20:14.000
I don't know if we used clip-flords or we had a table, but churches have all that.

01:20:14.000 --> 01:20:16.000
And we'd tell people to come to the back.

01:20:16.000 --> 01:20:17.000
And I would have people...

01:20:17.000 --> 01:20:19.000
I'd be one of the folks signing folks up.

01:20:19.000 --> 01:20:20.000
Helping them fill this in.

01:20:20.000 --> 01:20:22.000
A lot of people couldn't be the right.

01:20:22.000 --> 01:20:25.000
And so we'd be filling it in for them.

01:20:25.000 --> 01:20:31.000
And I think I even carried this to bars sometimes.

01:20:31.000 --> 01:20:33.000
I believe I did.

01:20:33.000 --> 01:20:34.000
Yeah.

01:20:34.000 --> 01:20:35.000
Because that was one of my venues.

01:20:35.000 --> 01:20:41.000
Which meant since I got up at sunrise and I didn't do a lot of sleeping.

01:20:41.000 --> 01:20:43.000
Lest it kept you busy.

01:20:43.000 --> 01:20:44.000
Yeah.

01:20:44.000 --> 01:20:47.000
Were there things that were hard about being in Mississippi

01:20:47.000 --> 01:20:53.000
or things that also you found particularly rewarding?

01:20:53.000 --> 01:20:56.000
Well, the whole thing was rewarding.

01:20:56.000 --> 01:20:57.000
I mean, in its total.

01:20:57.000 --> 01:20:59.000
And we had fun, too.

01:20:59.000 --> 01:21:01.000
I've told people that...

01:21:01.000 --> 01:21:07.000
I mean, I know it must have been one of the most horrible things in the world to be in a concentration camp.

01:21:07.000 --> 01:21:10.000
But I'm sure people found moments of enjoyment.

01:21:10.000 --> 01:21:13.000
I mean, certainly we had relations.

01:21:13.000 --> 01:21:16.000
I'm talking about intimate relations.

01:21:16.000 --> 01:21:26.000
And we danced and we laughed and got our ass beat up.

01:21:26.000 --> 01:21:28.000
But there were plenty of good times.

01:21:28.000 --> 01:21:31.000
It wasn't just all serious.

01:21:31.000 --> 01:21:33.000
There was a lot of good times.

01:21:33.000 --> 01:21:37.000
And the songs got people pumped up really good.

01:21:37.000 --> 01:21:39.000
I mean, people sang songs in jail.

01:21:39.000 --> 01:21:41.000
They sang songs in the field.

01:21:41.000 --> 01:21:44.000
They sang songs in churches.

01:21:44.000 --> 01:21:46.000
Were you ever a song leader?

01:21:46.000 --> 01:21:48.000
Oh, everybody laughed.

01:21:48.000 --> 01:21:49.000
I mean, I still...

01:21:49.000 --> 01:21:53.000
We are soldiers in the Army.

01:21:53.000 --> 01:21:55.000
We have to fight.

01:21:55.000 --> 01:21:57.000
Perhaps we have to die.

01:21:57.000 --> 01:21:59.000
We have to hold up.

01:21:59.000 --> 01:22:01.000
The blood stained banner.

01:22:01.000 --> 01:22:05.000
Have to hold it up until we die.

01:22:05.000 --> 01:22:07.000
I was the bass.

01:22:07.000 --> 01:22:11.000
Yeah.

01:22:11.000 --> 01:22:13.000
And they went on forever.

01:22:13.000 --> 01:22:15.000
And the freedom singers used to come by.

01:22:15.000 --> 01:22:17.000
They tore all us out.

01:22:17.000 --> 01:22:19.000
And they were wonderful.

01:22:19.000 --> 01:22:20.000
Yeah.

01:22:20.000 --> 01:22:23.000
So, are there...

01:22:23.000 --> 01:22:26.000
You mentioned Lee Bankhead and a few other people.

01:22:26.000 --> 01:22:31.000
Are there other people that you spend a lot of time working with that you can tell us about?

01:22:31.000 --> 01:22:34.000
I can't say any name.

01:22:34.000 --> 01:22:37.000
And I've tried to call his name.

01:22:37.000 --> 01:22:40.000
I lost it about 10 years ago maybe.

01:22:40.000 --> 01:22:43.000
Fenway Ham is nephew and I used to do a lot together.

01:22:43.000 --> 01:22:46.000
We used to, as a matter of fact, he...

01:22:46.000 --> 01:22:50.000
You know, I was the ones who were in Delta Pines plantation.

01:22:50.000 --> 01:22:55.000
We went to Yazoo City together and got our asses right out of there.

01:22:55.000 --> 01:22:58.000
Can you tell us about those two Delta Pines and Yazoo?

01:22:58.000 --> 01:23:01.000
Well, I wish I could tell you his name.

01:23:01.000 --> 01:23:04.000
But it seems not to be there.

01:23:04.000 --> 01:23:07.000
I remember after Delta Plines won...

01:23:07.000 --> 01:23:09.000
He...

01:23:09.000 --> 01:23:11.000
Okay, Delta Pines, we went there.

01:23:11.000 --> 01:23:14.000
Oh, yeah, because there's a couple of good stories.

01:23:14.000 --> 01:23:17.000
Delta Pines was a plantation.

01:23:17.000 --> 01:23:21.000
The old-fashioned plantation that had cabins that people lived in, sharecroppers.

01:23:21.000 --> 01:23:22.000
They basically were.

01:23:22.000 --> 01:23:24.000
Although, sharecroppers, not supposed to exist.

01:23:24.000 --> 01:23:26.000
And we were doing voter registration.

01:23:26.000 --> 01:23:28.000
We couldn't have done union organizing.

01:23:28.000 --> 01:23:29.000
We had...

01:23:29.000 --> 01:23:30.000
It wasn't...

01:23:30.000 --> 01:23:32.000
That's the sort of place we could have done that.

01:23:32.000 --> 01:23:35.000
We could have done it, you briefly, before the interview about it.

01:23:35.000 --> 01:23:39.000
That's where we met some older people down by the river

01:23:39.000 --> 01:23:41.000
who were living in these...

01:23:41.000 --> 01:23:42.000
These shacks.

01:23:42.000 --> 01:23:44.000
And they were talking about...

01:23:44.000 --> 01:23:50.000
Oh, we were the same group that had come to organize to get people registered to vote before.

01:23:50.000 --> 01:23:52.000
Nobody's been here before.

01:23:52.000 --> 01:23:54.000
This is SNCC with everyone.

01:23:54.000 --> 01:23:58.000
With everyone's stupid enough or tough enough or whatever to go in there.

01:23:58.000 --> 01:24:01.000
And I talked to them and I talked to them about when it was...

01:24:01.000 --> 01:24:04.000
I thought it was in the 40s or the 30s.

01:24:04.000 --> 01:24:07.000
I mean, they didn't know when they were old enough and of course they were old then.

01:24:07.000 --> 01:24:09.000
And that...

01:24:09.000 --> 01:24:11.000
The Communist Party had...

01:24:11.000 --> 01:24:16.000
Because when I said the word Communist, I knew enough of politics since I was reading.

01:24:16.000 --> 01:24:17.000
And it...

01:24:17.000 --> 01:24:18.000
No, I didn't know it was Communist Party then.

01:24:18.000 --> 01:24:20.000
I know they'd come in and float boats.

01:24:20.000 --> 01:24:22.000
I actually researched it later after I got out of the South.

01:24:22.000 --> 01:24:26.000
In fact, there was CP, Communist Party, who had come down to Mississippi

01:24:26.000 --> 01:24:28.000
to register people to vote.

01:24:28.000 --> 01:24:33.000
And then they came down to the river and would stop it where they saw houses.

01:24:33.000 --> 01:24:37.000
But so I realized then that we weren't the first.

01:24:37.000 --> 01:24:40.000
I mean, the 60s wasn't the beginning of it.

01:24:40.000 --> 01:24:44.000
So were they more receptive because they had this memory of earlier people?

01:24:44.000 --> 01:24:46.000
Well, they seemed receptive.

01:24:46.000 --> 01:24:51.000
But these particular people were simply felt they were too old.

01:24:51.000 --> 01:24:52.000
And how would they get out there?

01:24:52.000 --> 01:24:54.000
They didn't have any transportation.

01:24:54.000 --> 01:24:57.000
You had to go to whatever town was close and I'd have to look on the map I've forgotten.

01:24:57.000 --> 01:25:01.000
But they hadn't had transportation so they couldn't basically get off the plantation.

01:25:01.000 --> 01:25:03.000
I mean, there was no way.

01:25:03.000 --> 01:25:06.000
Somewhere along the line somebody dropped a dime on somebody called.

01:25:06.000 --> 01:25:11.000
And so there were these people driving up and down in trucks looking for us.

01:25:11.000 --> 01:25:13.000
And we left our car.

01:25:13.000 --> 01:25:15.000
We'd walked in and left our car.

01:25:15.000 --> 01:25:17.000
We wouldn't be seen.

01:25:17.000 --> 01:25:21.000
And so we were hiding out for several days.

01:25:21.000 --> 01:25:24.000
And I almost said his name.

01:25:24.000 --> 01:25:28.000
I remember when we got back, his hair was so nice.

01:25:28.000 --> 01:25:30.000
He couldn't get a brush or comb through it.

01:25:30.000 --> 01:25:32.000
And he had to shave his head.

01:25:32.000 --> 01:25:36.000
He had to get it because he had something with a short afro.

01:25:36.000 --> 01:25:37.000
Poor guy.

01:25:37.000 --> 01:25:39.000
And mine was pretty funky too.

01:25:39.000 --> 01:25:41.000
We hadn't washed and done anything.

01:25:41.000 --> 01:25:44.000
We'd been eating uncooked greens and stuff like that for three days.

01:25:44.000 --> 01:25:47.000
Hiding in ditches and ditches are not fun to hide in.

01:25:47.000 --> 01:25:49.000
We went to Yazoo City.

01:25:49.000 --> 01:25:52.000
I don't know how they, I guess they knew the car.

01:25:52.000 --> 01:25:55.000
And the cops had lists of SNCC cars.

01:25:55.000 --> 01:25:57.000
And that was always a problem.

01:25:57.000 --> 01:26:02.000
And the cops just met us and said, you know, if you don't turn around and leave,

01:26:02.000 --> 01:26:04.000
then you're going straight to jail.

01:26:04.000 --> 01:26:06.000
We'll keep you in jail for several months.

01:26:06.000 --> 01:26:09.000
And we said, okay, we'll turn around and leave and we'll have to do it.

01:26:09.000 --> 01:26:12.000
I know Mrs. Hammerhead, many brothers and sisters.

01:26:12.000 --> 01:26:14.000
So I imagine she had quite a few nephews.

01:26:14.000 --> 01:26:18.000
But is there anything you can tell us about that we might help us track down his name

01:26:18.000 --> 01:26:23.000
if we can try to look into it?

01:26:23.000 --> 01:26:24.000
No.

01:26:24.000 --> 01:26:26.000
I don't even know his father's name.

01:26:26.000 --> 01:26:27.000
I mean, I probably did.

01:26:27.000 --> 01:26:31.000
I mean, I knew his family and I knew every, I knew, I mean, if I can't remember him,

01:26:31.000 --> 01:26:35.000
and he used to stay in the office with me.

01:26:35.000 --> 01:26:39.000
And I wondered because I thought maybe, trying to find out if he's still alive

01:26:39.000 --> 01:26:41.000
and to reach out.

01:26:41.000 --> 01:26:43.000
And I didn't think about him for a long time.

01:26:43.000 --> 01:26:47.000
You know, it was just part of memories.

01:26:47.000 --> 01:26:49.000
I guess it was hard for me to leave.

01:26:49.000 --> 01:26:53.000
Once I left, you know, part of me wanted to go back.

01:26:53.000 --> 01:26:56.000
And part of me wanted to keep in touch and see people.

01:26:56.000 --> 01:26:58.000
He couldn't make phone calls, I said, you know.

01:26:58.000 --> 01:27:00.000
And a lot of people didn't even have phones.

01:27:00.000 --> 01:27:02.000
And, you know, cell phones were so much, you know,

01:27:02.000 --> 01:27:06.000
it changed the world as, as email.

01:27:06.000 --> 01:27:08.000
And people didn't write much.

01:27:08.000 --> 01:27:10.000
I mean, not many people wrote things.

01:27:10.000 --> 01:27:12.000
So, uh, Dictograph.

01:27:12.000 --> 01:27:13.000
That's the word.

01:27:13.000 --> 01:27:14.000
Dictograph.

01:27:14.000 --> 01:27:23.000
What, um, why, why, how did you come to leave?

01:27:23.000 --> 01:27:24.000
I figured it was time.

01:27:24.000 --> 01:27:29.000
There were a lot of, uh, a lot of groups coming in.

01:27:29.000 --> 01:27:33.000
Uh, uh, uh, Delta Ministries was in doing a lot of work.

01:27:33.000 --> 01:27:37.000
There were a lot of groups where a lot of, uh,

01:27:37.000 --> 01:27:41.000
we got a lot of volunteers about the time I left.

01:27:41.000 --> 01:27:47.000
And, um, I was up north doing fundraising.

01:27:47.000 --> 01:27:51.000
And I started to go down when I got, when I go back, I said,

01:27:51.000 --> 01:27:52.000
you know, I'm not sure.

01:27:52.000 --> 01:27:55.000
And I talked to people and they were doing also stuff.

01:27:55.000 --> 01:27:58.000
And I didn't think I was, you know, key anymore.

01:27:58.000 --> 01:27:59.000
I didn't think I was needed that much.

01:27:59.000 --> 01:28:01.000
And a lot, a lot of volunteers.

01:28:01.000 --> 01:28:05.000
And I said, it's time to move on.

01:28:05.000 --> 01:28:08.000
And I also bumped into, I was in D.C.

01:28:08.000 --> 01:28:13.000
And they were, uh, because I, I'd done short order cooking and, you know,

01:28:13.000 --> 01:28:15.000
done all that to myself through college.

01:28:15.000 --> 01:28:17.000
And they were starting a union.

01:28:17.000 --> 01:28:19.000
I mean, not there was a one starting them.

01:28:19.000 --> 01:28:25.000
The, uh, Cook's hotels and restaurant workers union was doing a big,

01:28:25.000 --> 01:28:28.000
uh, they were striking all over the city.

01:28:28.000 --> 01:28:31.000
And, um, I happened to be talking to them.

01:28:31.000 --> 01:28:34.000
They said, well, you know, love to have your work for us.

01:28:34.000 --> 01:28:38.000
I mean, they paid, they paid a real salary, by the way.

01:28:38.000 --> 01:28:42.000
And, you know, and, you know, I said, you know, and, um,

01:28:42.000 --> 01:28:44.000
so I, I stayed.

01:28:44.000 --> 01:28:48.000
And then, then I thought after the strike, we, we did pretty well.

01:28:48.000 --> 01:28:51.000
We won some places, some places went non-union.

01:28:51.000 --> 01:28:53.000
And I thought of going back.

01:28:53.000 --> 01:28:56.000
And of course, by that time there was a lot of, uh, pan-African stuff.

01:28:56.000 --> 01:28:59.000
And, and, and some of that already had changed.

01:28:59.000 --> 01:29:00.000
And I thought that was good.

01:29:00.000 --> 01:29:03.000
I mean, I, I thought the pan-Africanism was good.

01:29:03.000 --> 01:29:09.000
And, um, and that it needed to be more of all the black movement.

01:29:09.000 --> 01:29:10.000
Um-hmm,

01:29:10.000 --> 01:29:15.000
And so you decided to stay in DC, DC area then?

01:29:15.000 --> 01:29:16.000
I stayed in DC.

01:29:16.000 --> 01:29:18.000
I, then I started traveling.

01:29:18.000 --> 01:29:20.000
I went, I decided it was time to go to Mexico.

01:29:20.000 --> 01:29:23.000
I spent a lot of time in Mexico and I traveled around Mexico.

01:29:23.000 --> 01:29:27.000
And, um, did a lot of things with traditional native religion.

01:29:27.000 --> 01:29:30.000
Um, got really interested.

01:29:30.000 --> 01:29:34.000
I can, I can marry you in D.C. and California.

01:29:34.000 --> 01:29:36.000
I mean, I'm a priest.

01:29:36.000 --> 01:29:38.000
How is that?

01:29:38.000 --> 01:29:42.000
Um, and I got really into some native cultural stuff.

01:29:42.000 --> 01:29:46.000
And I traveled other countries and, and Central South America.

01:29:46.000 --> 01:29:48.000
And, um, traveled on the States.

01:29:48.000 --> 01:29:49.000
I hadn't seen this.

01:29:49.000 --> 01:29:50.000
I'd, I'd, I'd, traveled some of the States.

01:29:50.000 --> 01:29:54.000
But I got, you know, but I'm around the States and worked, where I went.

01:29:54.000 --> 01:29:59.000
And I worked in Foundaries in Minneapolis and, and, and, ranches and Arizona.

01:29:59.000 --> 01:30:05.000
And, you know, just, for a while, just was trying to figure out and always doing political stuff.

01:30:05.000 --> 01:30:06.000
Um-hmm.

01:30:06.000 --> 01:30:13.000
How do you think the, I mean, I know you've been an organizer and an activist.

01:30:13.000 --> 01:30:15.000
It seems your entire adult life.

01:30:15.000 --> 01:30:21.000
How do you think that work in the, the sort of black freedom movement and in Mississippi?

01:30:21.000 --> 01:30:23.000
Influence that?

01:30:23.000 --> 01:30:25.000
Talked me.

01:30:25.000 --> 01:30:27.000
Yeah.

01:30:27.000 --> 01:30:37.000
Um, it taught me, uh, how to organize with people who I may not have had something in common with, to start with.

01:30:37.000 --> 01:30:39.000
Do we all have things in common, of course?

01:30:39.000 --> 01:30:43.000
And I guess I focused on that.

01:30:43.000 --> 01:30:51.000
It broadened my horizons and ways I never could have imagined when I went down.

01:30:51.000 --> 01:30:56.000
I don't know, that make me, and you know, I guess I was always, I would never really good with fear.

01:30:56.000 --> 01:30:59.000
I mean, I don't have good sense about what I'm supposed to be afraid.

01:30:59.000 --> 01:31:01.000
I always had that problem.

01:31:01.000 --> 01:31:04.000
You know, I went with fire workers and they were beating us.

01:31:04.000 --> 01:31:09.000
For a long time, I was an iron worker doing towers and bridges and people who say, doesn't bother you.

01:31:09.000 --> 01:31:11.000
Most of them happen as you follow.

01:31:11.000 --> 01:31:13.000
The ground will stop you.

01:31:13.000 --> 01:31:15.000
Indeed.

01:31:15.000 --> 01:31:19.000
It is the fall that hurts us as a sudden stop.

01:31:19.000 --> 01:31:32.000
Um, and so I guess it, I don't know if it taught me to have gumption to do what I think is right or maybe I already had that, but it certainly cemented it.

01:31:32.000 --> 01:31:37.000
So, you know, if I really think this is the right thing to do, I'm a little bit of a bulldog.

01:31:37.000 --> 01:31:39.000
Yeah.

01:31:39.000 --> 01:31:40.000
Yeah.

01:31:40.000 --> 01:31:45.000
What was it like to go back and work on Espy's campaign?

01:31:45.000 --> 01:31:48.000
It was really a trip.

01:31:48.000 --> 01:31:54.000
Um, and we took, well, we took a van full of volunteers down.

01:31:54.000 --> 01:32:00.000
None of them, some of them had been to the South some, but none had been to Mississippi, that part.

01:32:00.000 --> 01:32:03.000
And I mean, I even, as I said, drove by, saw the shack.

01:32:03.000 --> 01:32:04.000
I said, I lived in that.

01:32:04.000 --> 01:32:08.000
I mean, this isn't big enough for my dog to live with you.

01:32:08.000 --> 01:32:13.000
Um, it was, I mean, the South had changed, but hadn't changed.

01:32:13.000 --> 01:32:29.000
I mean, many things in, in, uh, in jacks, well, I wasn't in Jackson that much, because he was running in basically the same areas I worked in, which I think was a third congressional fourth.

01:32:29.000 --> 01:32:33.000
It might have, well, you know, it changed a number of times, but it was the Delta District.

01:32:33.000 --> 01:32:34.000
Yeah.

01:32:34.000 --> 01:32:36.000
It might have been the second congressional district.

01:32:36.000 --> 01:32:37.000
That's the rings of Delta.

01:32:37.000 --> 01:32:38.000
Yeah.

01:32:38.000 --> 01:32:43.000
Anyway, uh, so it was the same area.

01:32:43.000 --> 01:32:54.000
And in Cleveland, there was an amazing, I think it was a, the sheriff was black or something, an amazing amount of changes in those in that time.

01:32:54.000 --> 01:33:05.000
Once you got out in the rural areas, uh, because I tried to go to rural areas and go to these houses where, you know, no, no sidewalks,

01:33:05.000 --> 01:33:12.000
the ditch runs down in front of the house and, you know, there's a little bridge across it and it's up on these little concrete stills.

01:33:12.000 --> 01:33:17.000
That's what all of the black neighborhood in Jackson and, and Cleveland was like when I was there.

01:33:17.000 --> 01:33:28.000
You could tell when I was in Cleveland, and in most of the South, what was black and what was white, because streets were paved and they had underground sewers and in the black area they didn't.

01:33:28.000 --> 01:33:34.000
Um, it, there were a lot of teachers making good money and the schools were interested.

01:33:34.000 --> 01:33:39.000
Great. So they were making the same money as the white tea or, I don't know, same, but they were making good money.

01:33:39.000 --> 01:33:45.000
But then in the rural areas, it wasn't, um, working on those cramp rain was thrilling.

01:33:45.000 --> 01:33:52.000
He won, it was 82 votes and I told people in the way back every one of us can say we changed.

01:33:52.000 --> 01:33:59.000
We got 82 people to vote. And so every one of us can say if I wasn't there, that wouldn't happen.

01:33:59.000 --> 01:34:03.000
And I've used that example many times since then.

01:34:03.000 --> 01:34:10.000
Yeah. How did you connect it to his campaign? How did you get connected to his campaign?

01:34:10.000 --> 01:34:16.000
Probably to the Democratic Party. Yeah. You know, I've worked with the Democratic Party and they put out a call. They needed help.

01:34:16.000 --> 01:34:25.000
Yeah. And we organized, um, we had, we, yeah, because the Democratic Party, I think, rented the van.

01:34:25.000 --> 01:34:31.000
We had one of those stretch vans. I think we seats 12 and probably had 11 or 12 people in it. We had jammed.

01:34:31.000 --> 01:34:36.000
Yeah. Yeah. Must have been a nice feeling to have them win.

01:34:36.000 --> 01:34:38.000
Oh, yeah. It was incredible.

01:34:38.000 --> 01:34:45.000
I remember I've heard stories that when Amsy Moore and Bob Moses first started talking about voter registration and political work,

01:34:45.000 --> 01:34:52.000
which led to SNCC's campaign in Mississippi, they were talking about having a representative from the Delta in doubt.

01:34:52.000 --> 01:35:00.000
And Mike Espy was the first. Yeah. Yeah. Was it a full circle?

01:35:00.000 --> 01:35:08.000
So where are some of the highlights or things that you think are particularly important that you've done since then?

01:35:08.000 --> 01:35:14.000
I, as you say, it's a, it's a long, long list.

01:35:14.000 --> 01:35:16.000
Okay. So what is this button?

01:35:16.000 --> 01:35:22.000
That's, um, one of the official buttons put out by the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party.

01:35:22.000 --> 01:35:28.000
And, um, I may have one of the only left around in the country.

01:35:28.000 --> 01:35:36.000
People have tried to get it many times. I've got a number of buttons from back then. Core buttons and SNCC buttons and,

01:35:36.000 --> 01:35:39.000
um, and things like that.

01:35:39.000 --> 01:35:43.000
No, one SNCC, and finds out about them, they'll be knocking on your door.

01:35:43.000 --> 01:35:47.000
I've actually wondered what to do with it. There are a number of libraries.

01:35:47.000 --> 01:35:55.000
I've given them, probably going to give them to my daughter, um, who gets all sorts of stuff.

01:35:55.000 --> 01:35:57.000
Actually, I made for her birthday one time.

01:35:57.000 --> 01:36:00.000
Fortunately, we didn't have T-shirts back then. Yeah.

01:36:01.000 --> 01:36:07.000
But I made her a T-shirt from things I've done since then, with political events and marches on Washington and stuff like that.

01:36:07.000 --> 01:36:09.000
I made, I took them all, made her quilt.

01:36:09.000 --> 01:36:10.000
Wow.

01:36:10.000 --> 01:36:16.000
So they're also together and I showed up this quilt. So she has this quilt that, part of my political history.

01:36:16.000 --> 01:36:20.000
It's too bad she has it. Otherwise we could take a look at it.

01:36:20.000 --> 01:36:25.000
I probably have some pictures of it, but I'd have to find them. They're digital. So I could probably dig them out.

01:36:25.000 --> 01:36:26.000
Yeah. Yeah.

01:36:26.000 --> 01:36:28.000
Okay. So.

01:36:29.000 --> 01:36:34.000
Oh, I'm sorry. I can't. So so long for me seeing anymore.

01:36:34.000 --> 01:36:35.000
I don't know.

01:36:35.000 --> 01:36:38.000
That's okay.

01:36:38.000 --> 01:36:44.000
Occasionally I'm downstairs. I've been wearing glasses for many, many years, but occasionally I come downstairs and wake up and I'm like,

01:36:44.000 --> 01:36:46.000
good to have a upstairs. I said, wait a minute.

01:36:46.000 --> 01:36:48.000
I can't see anything what's going on.

01:36:48.000 --> 01:36:49.000
How did I do that?

01:36:49.000 --> 01:36:50.000
Yeah.

01:36:50.000 --> 01:36:59.000
So can you talk about Ms. Hamer in a mass meeting?

01:36:59.000 --> 01:37:08.000
I thought we did that. She was, she was a very powerful speaker, really powerful speaker.

01:37:08.000 --> 01:37:15.000
And she dominated the room.

01:37:15.000 --> 01:37:22.000
And I think everyone, I mean, people have seen her and there are lots of movies I've seen her, you know, keep on keeping on and stuff like that.

01:37:22.000 --> 01:37:32.000
More I think impressive was how she dominated meetings. And she was in a number of meetings with all of the major,

01:37:32.000 --> 01:37:39.000
major, snake people that you hear about. And nobody ever went against her. They tried to, but it didn't work.

01:37:39.000 --> 01:37:49.000
And I've been told a number of times is what they simply do is say, well, we're just not going to disagree whether we're just going to go do our thing because you couldn't.

01:37:49.000 --> 01:37:50.000
She was a very powerful person.

01:37:50.000 --> 01:37:56.000
Can you remember any examples of what some of the differences might have been?

01:37:56.000 --> 01:37:59.000
Oh, no, not. I don't.

01:37:59.000 --> 01:38:11.000
Oh, I'm trying to dig up some old memories. They were political, whether we have a demonstration or which town we would be should focus on to try and do voter registration.

01:38:11.000 --> 01:38:14.000
Most of it wasn't union stuff.

01:38:14.000 --> 01:38:22.000
And some of it was, I guess, tactical for the Democratic Party, the Freedom Democratic Party.

01:38:22.000 --> 01:38:29.000
Whether we, I think at one time, we were trying to run a candidate and whether it was going to eat.

01:38:29.000 --> 01:38:38.000
And we could use that for just somebody who it was registered because not many people registered at that time.

01:38:38.000 --> 01:38:43.000
I don't remember who that was. I got a big picture of him in my mind, but it was a male.

01:38:43.000 --> 01:38:58.000
And somebody was going to try and run and I remember whether it was a waste of our effort to try and do that was symbolic, but it was important enough to do.

01:38:58.000 --> 01:39:01.000
And to be honest, I don't remember which side she was on.

01:39:01.000 --> 01:39:06.000
I don't think we did it, which means probably she wasn't supportive of it.

01:39:06.000 --> 01:39:14.000
I mean, I do know that there were a number of symbolic, largely symbolic candidates early on.

01:39:14.000 --> 01:39:26.000
And I guess you would have been leaving Mississippi right about the time that the first elections took place where there were significant black voters after the Voting Rights Act.

01:39:26.000 --> 01:39:32.000
Yeah. I mean, but we used to do so many things to those are the details about.

01:39:32.000 --> 01:39:38.000
You know, they had some places they wanted you to tell them the beans were in the jar and some places they had to interpret the Constitution.

01:39:38.000 --> 01:39:48.000
And we, you know, go over the Constitution line by line, hour by hour, and very few people would they accept.

01:39:48.000 --> 01:39:51.000
A couple they did. We had, you know, a handful here in their register.

01:39:51.000 --> 01:40:10.000
Do you, do you remember or have a sense of what the impact was like on the ground in Mississippi after the Voting Rights Act passed, how that changed your work or it changed if you weren't working on voter registration, then how it changed the context for that?

01:40:11.000 --> 01:40:16.000
When I left, it still was hard to register voters.

01:40:16.000 --> 01:40:24.000
The FBI was mostly Southern crackers.

01:40:24.000 --> 01:40:33.000
And I mean, you know, when the FBI would come after, you know, there was a beating or something like that interview you, you know that it was going to happen.

01:40:33.000 --> 01:40:42.000
It wasn't so mostly they upheld the system. So we didn't, we had not seen any change by the time I left.

01:40:42.000 --> 01:40:48.000
And I guess one of the things I regretted, by the way, was staying and seeing some of that come to fruition.

01:40:48.000 --> 01:41:02.000
But a lot, as I said, a lot of people were coming down and there were a lot of people, there was enough money that people were making salaries and holding events that were funded.

01:41:02.000 --> 01:41:05.000
And it was hard to compete.

01:41:05.000 --> 01:41:08.000
So who do you know who these folks are or what the mechanism for?

01:41:08.000 --> 01:41:10.000
Well, Delta Ministry said a number down.

01:41:10.000 --> 01:41:14.000
Delta Ministry said a number down. And there was some other groups too.

01:41:14.000 --> 01:41:27.000
Yeah, yeah. Well, and I know, and this has been different part of the state, but I know that once, you know, in a little bit later, there's once Charles Evers uses FAAD, establishes FAAD as his base.

01:41:27.000 --> 01:41:35.000
There's a lot of interest in some of his political campaigns. So I know that the campaigns were drawing outside attention.

01:41:35.000 --> 01:41:42.000
Yeah, they were, and money and people, which is a good thing. I mean, things changed.

01:41:42.000 --> 01:41:48.000
A lot of, I think, you know, I don't want a bad mouth any other organizations.

01:41:48.000 --> 01:41:51.000
Yeah. It's not something I wanted to.

01:41:51.000 --> 01:41:55.000
You mentioned the poverty programs or Head Start.

01:41:55.000 --> 01:41:59.000
Did you work closely or collaboratively with any of them?

01:41:59.000 --> 01:42:01.000
I'm sure. I mean, everybody did everything.

01:42:01.000 --> 01:42:03.000
Yeah. Yeah. And that's the whole thing.

01:42:03.000 --> 01:42:15.000
I even taught, you know, math and some of them, but getting funding, getting a building, doing all that organizing, it was giving the kids a Head Start.

01:42:15.000 --> 01:42:19.000
And I think everybody believed in it. Everybody worked on it.

01:42:19.000 --> 01:42:23.000
It was just one of the many things that people did.

01:42:23.000 --> 01:42:29.000
We were 24 hours a day, seven days a week.

01:42:29.000 --> 01:42:35.000
We were available bodies while most people had to work or had a bunch of kids they had to take care of.

01:42:35.000 --> 01:42:41.000
So a lot of the stuff that needed to get done, you know, we could help get done.

01:42:41.000 --> 01:42:52.000
I was a reasonable carpenter. So, you know, I remember we were fixing some building up and, you know, putting up partitions and stuff like that.

01:42:52.000 --> 01:42:55.000
So everybody just pitched in, did what they good.

01:42:55.000 --> 01:43:01.000
Yeah. So what are some of the, I think I just asked this and then we took the break.

01:43:01.000 --> 01:43:08.000
But do you want to pick out some of the things that you've worked on and some of the many things you've worked on?

01:43:08.000 --> 01:43:15.000
Well, I have a per chance for working on failed causes, I guess.

01:43:15.000 --> 01:43:20.000
I might work on Jesse Jackson's two campaigns, for instance.

01:43:20.000 --> 01:43:27.000
I designed a way of building ferrocement fishing boats after the Revolution in Grenada.

01:43:27.000 --> 01:43:29.000
I was very involved in Grenada.

01:43:29.000 --> 01:43:33.000
And it was a wonderful, wonderful place.

01:43:33.000 --> 01:43:40.000
They had a true bottom up government.

01:43:40.000 --> 01:43:44.000
They had local community that would feed into regional communities that feed up.

01:43:44.000 --> 01:43:47.000
So the government they established was that way.

01:43:47.000 --> 01:43:50.000
They abolished, for instance, prostitution.

01:43:50.000 --> 01:43:52.000
They didn't do it by abolishing prostitution.

01:43:52.000 --> 01:43:57.000
But I said, anybody who's in the trade, you want a job, we will find you something to do.

01:43:57.000 --> 01:44:00.000
There was nobody left.

01:44:01.000 --> 01:44:04.000
How did you get involved in that?

01:44:04.000 --> 01:44:06.000
I don't know.

01:44:06.000 --> 01:44:08.000
I heard about it.

01:44:08.000 --> 01:44:14.000
Of course, you know, I've been to Cuba and I heard about it and I said I'd go there and I was really impressed.

01:44:14.000 --> 01:44:16.000
And I talked a lot.

01:44:16.000 --> 01:44:20.000
I worked in the fishing villages for a little bit because I'd lived.

01:44:20.000 --> 01:44:22.000
I'd already lived in the Caribbean when I went there.

01:44:22.000 --> 01:44:29.000
I lived in Trinidad for a while, just went to Trinidad and Barbados and, you know, Dominican and places.

01:44:30.000 --> 01:44:31.000
Haiti.

01:44:31.000 --> 01:44:35.000
And so I'd already been to the Caribbean because I traveled.

01:44:35.000 --> 01:44:41.000
And so I had a way of building ferro-summit fishing boats and we were going to be building.

01:44:41.000 --> 01:44:42.000
The government was going to be building.

01:44:42.000 --> 01:44:46.000
I was the director of the project and of course the U.S. invaded.

01:44:46.000 --> 01:44:53.000
I just like to work on campaigns that don't work or issues that don't work.

01:44:53.000 --> 01:44:57.000
I was his national coordinator of states.

01:44:57.000 --> 01:45:00.000
I was in Fume.

01:45:00.000 --> 01:45:08.000
I was his, as I said, county coordinator and he didn't win either.

01:45:08.000 --> 01:45:10.000
We lost five.

01:45:10.000 --> 01:45:15.000
Well, three percentage points and they had almost ten times as much money as we did.

01:45:15.000 --> 01:45:17.000
The Democratic support to candidate.

01:45:17.000 --> 01:45:18.000
One of those.

01:45:18.000 --> 01:45:20.000
One of those moral victories, right?

01:45:20.000 --> 01:45:22.000
Yeah, no.

01:45:22.000 --> 01:45:24.000
More victories.

01:45:24.000 --> 01:45:33.000
Anyway, so I worked on all things like immigration issues and Palestinian issues.

01:45:33.000 --> 01:45:34.000
We did win too.

01:45:34.000 --> 01:45:43.000
We won the immigration and the Dream Act in Maryland and of course, gay marriage in Maryland.

01:45:43.000 --> 01:45:50.000
So I've had some but most of them, you know, and I do a lot of work with elected officials.

01:45:50.000 --> 01:45:59.000
And I think I've done a lot of things in the community over the years supported issues of empowerment in the community that have been successful.

01:45:59.000 --> 01:46:11.000
I think that people coming out of the movement have different and changing and complex thinking about the relationship between organizing work and traditional politics.

01:46:11.000 --> 01:46:12.000
Oh, yeah.

01:46:12.000 --> 01:46:15.000
I don't know if traditional politics is the right word.

01:46:15.000 --> 01:46:21.000
But working through the political process and how effective that can be, you seem to have done both.

01:46:21.000 --> 01:46:22.000
Yeah, I do both.

01:46:22.000 --> 01:46:26.000
And I've been in certainly those discussions numerous times.

01:46:26.000 --> 01:46:36.000
The biggest or one of a good example, I think of that that I've mentioned many times is I did a lot work with the zapatistas and Chepis.

01:46:36.000 --> 01:46:38.000
And you know about that.

01:46:38.000 --> 01:46:41.000
Do you want to just give a little bit of an introduction?

01:46:41.000 --> 01:46:58.000
Oh, okay. For people who don't know, there is a lot of discrimination in Mexico against native people and it's usually run by people, misty toe or angles who run the government.

01:46:58.000 --> 01:47:10.000
And the zapatistas are mostly mine and several other tribal groups in the Chappas Park, which is a southern, south, eastern tip.

01:47:10.000 --> 01:47:15.000
We're not quite all the way down to the Yucatan of Mexico.

01:47:16.000 --> 01:47:27.000
And they basically said there were a lot of land that was owned by non-resident landowners who lived in Mexico City and they just took it over.

01:47:27.000 --> 01:47:31.000
They said this is native land and they set up a government.

01:47:31.000 --> 01:47:37.000
And there was a lot of back and forth and especially the landowners would hire paramilitary police.

01:47:37.000 --> 01:47:44.000
And I went down to document several massacres and there were a lot of people who men and women and children killed.

01:47:44.000 --> 01:47:53.000
So it is a struggle that still goes on and they have what appears to be an independent land.

01:47:53.000 --> 01:47:56.000
But it's not totally independent.

01:47:56.000 --> 01:48:03.000
But they are making sure that the profits go to the people and I can give you lots of examples in Mexico.

01:48:03.000 --> 01:48:12.000
I was an El Salvador where the coffee pickers don't drink coffee because they can't afford it and they'll be attired if they take a coffee bean home.

01:48:12.000 --> 01:48:16.000
So they pick and coffee all day long but can't even drink coffee.

01:48:16.000 --> 01:48:28.000
Okay, getting back to we had and I was with a support group in the States because we can do more to help them some money and trying influence.

01:48:28.000 --> 01:48:39.000
And there was a situation going on with the federal police going in and doing a lot of mayhem.

01:48:39.000 --> 01:48:44.000
And we were you know crying and screaming about it all the political lefties I was with.

01:48:44.000 --> 01:48:51.000
And then we finally got to a friend friend of mine and somebody else's got to Kennedy.

01:48:51.000 --> 01:48:58.000
So the Kennedy when he was alive and his aide made a phone call and stopped it.

01:48:58.000 --> 01:49:03.000
Now that happened because people worked on those political campaigns.

01:49:04.000 --> 01:49:07.000
In Kennedy's case actually was a good enough guy.

01:49:07.000 --> 01:49:13.000
I have lots of elected officials that I can call up and say we need to look at this.

01:49:13.000 --> 01:49:15.000
We need to do something about it.

01:49:15.000 --> 01:49:19.000
They don't do it just because you're a nice guy or a nice woman.

01:49:19.000 --> 01:49:24.000
They do it because you can turn votes out and you will turn votes out.

01:49:24.000 --> 01:49:30.000
I'm a threat to you. You have to be able to say I will turn votes out and kick your butt out of office unless you get right.

01:49:30.000 --> 01:49:35.000
And the same thing for a lot of these issues.

01:49:35.000 --> 01:49:47.000
As I said we had got marriage equality and the Dream Act passed in Maryland because we did the grunt work of going out to the people and having them go back to the politicians.

01:49:47.000 --> 01:49:49.000
So it's both.

01:49:49.000 --> 01:49:52.000
I don't think you can do just one.

01:49:52.000 --> 01:49:58.000
I mean I'm as far out of the left as you can get but that you have to work within the system too.

01:49:58.000 --> 01:50:03.000
I remember what was it that used to say that revolution will not be televised.

01:50:03.000 --> 01:50:10.000
It's not televised and it didn't take place and you know and it's not going to in this country because they have.

01:50:10.000 --> 01:50:18.000
Someone's a strong enough leader that usually buy the mountains one way or another or assassinate if they do that too.

01:50:18.000 --> 01:50:23.000
What are the things that you're most interested in today?

01:50:23.000 --> 01:50:36.000
The Supreme Court decision of you know they just encased so everybody knows they just overturned part of the voting rights act and unfortunately there's no way you can affect the Supreme Court by doing political work.

01:50:36.000 --> 01:50:39.000
They seem to be in there for life.

01:50:39.000 --> 01:50:47.000
They did some decent things about K rights but only because I think they had no choice on that one.

01:50:47.000 --> 01:50:57.000
I'm interested whatever's happening. I'm always interested in the struggle, the Palestinian struggle and the struggles of people all over the world not just in the States anymore.

01:50:57.000 --> 01:51:09.000
I used to be when I was in the South I didn't look beyond the U.S. and now I'm going to the U.S. with all the problems all over.

01:51:09.000 --> 01:51:16.000
Was that that isolation that you talked about in the South or is that part of your own sort of growth and travel?

01:51:16.000 --> 01:51:24.000
Certainly the isolation. I remember who was it that came from Africa?

01:51:24.000 --> 01:51:26.000
There was a song. It was a so-

01:51:26.000 --> 01:51:28.000
O'Gingho, Dingo.

01:51:28.000 --> 01:51:36.000
Yes. And I mean Africa was then to me was just like this far place and I knew nothing about it.

01:51:36.000 --> 01:51:40.000
I knew Mexico and I knew down probably...

01:51:40.000 --> 01:51:45.000
I don't think I'd been South of Mexico in that part then.

01:51:45.000 --> 01:51:57.000
But you know all that far stuff and you knew about of course European history, everybody read that in school but there was no African history, no Central South American history, no Caribbean history.

01:51:57.000 --> 01:52:01.000
And it wasn't until I got...

01:52:01.000 --> 01:52:08.000
The South you certainly wouldn't learn about it except for that one time. I mean Africa was never mentioned in the news.

01:52:08.000 --> 01:52:11.000
And yeah it was personal growth.

01:52:11.000 --> 01:52:17.000
Were you part of conversations in SNCC about Africa and the international context?

01:52:17.000 --> 01:52:28.000
Some of them yes and I would put them in context of you know Native people...well actually it was probably more Latinos at the time.

01:52:28.000 --> 01:52:32.000
I wasn't that focused on the Native issues.

01:52:32.000 --> 01:52:43.000
Yeah I would say and you know there's a tie and I certainly appreciated people going back to their roots and it actually probably is.

01:52:43.000 --> 01:52:49.000
And it also affected a lot of other people. A lot of Latinos started to look at what that means.

01:52:49.000 --> 01:52:54.000
It wasn't just the Brown-Barrés that were doing it but the Larassa.

01:52:54.000 --> 01:52:58.000
And I was one of the original members of Larassa.

01:52:58.000 --> 01:53:00.000
Can you talk about that?

01:53:00.000 --> 01:53:08.000
I was a distant member. I mean I...when I was in California I was...but that's time I was in the East Coast.

01:53:08.000 --> 01:53:14.000
And probably along with it, Kristi Rodriguez who was my place sister.

01:53:14.000 --> 01:53:21.000
And she was...I know the people involved in it but I was just...you know...

01:53:21.000 --> 01:53:28.000
We by that time we had...phones were working. We did a lot of correspondence. Elect...

01:53:28.000 --> 01:53:33.000
No we didn't have the internet that when it started. God, my brain.

01:53:33.000 --> 01:53:39.000
You know it's hard to remember how you communicated. So we got...we'd write letters.

01:53:39.000 --> 01:53:46.000
Oh yeah I remember. Historians like that letter writing era.

01:53:46.000 --> 01:53:55.000
Yeah well if you could find the letters. I mean I...I actually...I've got boxes and boxes of that stuff.

01:53:55.000 --> 01:53:58.000
Up in the attic. Boy I'd give that away too.

01:53:58.000 --> 01:54:01.000
Is this personal correspondence and organizational papers?

01:54:01.000 --> 01:54:10.000
No correspondence with political organizations. I mean I was involved in so many political organizations.

01:54:10.000 --> 01:54:15.000
Yeah and I've actually found...I don't know...I've tried to give...do I...no I gave that away.

01:54:15.000 --> 01:54:20.000
I had some old SNCC stuff that was official comments and correspondence in the...

01:54:20.000 --> 01:54:24.000
But I gave it to one of the libraries. Yeah.

01:54:24.000 --> 01:54:30.000
Yeah I could. But it's all hard copy. I don't need...I need electronics so I can sort through it.

01:54:30.000 --> 01:54:32.000
Yeah.

01:54:36.000 --> 01:54:43.000
I don't know. I mean I do so many political things now as I said in the biography.

01:54:43.000 --> 01:54:50.000
I was sitting there and I could...I could copy. I could put on my glasses except I can't...you don't like me to do that.

01:54:50.000 --> 01:54:55.000
And look at some of them and I know I'm missing a whole lot of them.

01:54:55.000 --> 01:55:03.000
Worked on just numbers of political campaigns that worked in the Statehood Party when I got to D.C.,

01:55:03.000 --> 01:55:06.000
Because that seemed like a reasonable thing to do.

01:55:06.000 --> 01:55:10.000
Were there a lot of movement people involved in the Statehood?

01:55:10.000 --> 01:55:13.000
Yeah. We were local movement people.

01:55:13.000 --> 01:55:15.000
Local movement people.

01:55:15.000 --> 01:55:19.000
But I mean there were Julius Hobson was known for a lot of stuff. He was one of the key people.

01:55:19.000 --> 01:55:30.000
Josephine Butler was also part of the US Soviet Union Friendship Society.

01:55:30.000 --> 01:55:41.000
And...she passed away. There were three major people.

01:55:41.000 --> 01:55:50.000
Hilda Mason, who was well known as...I mean you probably crossed her name.

01:55:50.000 --> 01:55:55.000
She black and her husband was a lawyer and he was white.

01:55:55.000 --> 01:56:01.000
But she was doing a lot of civil rights stuff in the South and in the North.

01:56:01.000 --> 01:56:08.000
And those were three of the key people. They were all lefties.

01:56:08.000 --> 01:56:14.000
What are some of...are there other things that you'd like to talk about?

01:56:14.000 --> 01:56:21.000
Well I don't know that this is a forum to plead for change.

01:56:21.000 --> 01:56:25.000
But that's what I'm always worried about. It's empowerment of people.

01:56:25.000 --> 01:56:29.000
So that people get to make decisions for themselves.

01:56:29.000 --> 01:56:40.000
And I mean I note for instance that especially in the immigration as people...

01:56:40.000 --> 01:56:45.000
And people are saying, people shouldn't be able to come to this country.

01:56:45.000 --> 01:56:50.000
First of all I've got a nice sign over there. We don't recognize the borders.

01:56:50.000 --> 01:56:57.000
The borders are artificial and I don't know who invited the pilgrims here anyway.

01:56:57.000 --> 01:57:02.000
You want to talk about immigration issues. They weren't invited.

01:57:02.000 --> 01:57:10.000
The fact that it was even an article in the Washington Post editorial bio-etheno.

01:57:10.000 --> 01:57:15.000
And I think they're going to publish letter to the other railroad.

01:57:15.000 --> 01:57:22.000
And he was saying about, okay now we've made it because the politicians are paying attention to Latino issues.

01:57:22.000 --> 01:57:25.000
Look at the schools. Our kids are just doing terribly.

01:57:25.000 --> 01:57:28.000
And black kids aren't doing very well either.

01:57:28.000 --> 01:57:34.000
The problems of racism are still alive and well in this country.

01:57:34.000 --> 01:57:40.000
And we need to do something about it. I mean the Voting Rights Act is a very small part of it.

01:57:40.000 --> 01:57:44.000
But there needs to be some willingness to address it.

01:57:44.000 --> 01:57:48.000
People who thought Obama would do something about it, of course we're wrong.

01:57:48.000 --> 01:57:54.000
He's trying to, if anything, hide from the issue so he doesn't get thrown back at him.

01:57:54.000 --> 01:57:58.000
But there are just serious issues and a lot of them are issues of poverty.

01:57:58.000 --> 01:58:05.000
Not just ethnicity. And for one of the richest nations in the world...

01:58:05.000 --> 01:58:09.000
And of course it's the 99 percent. Well it's even worse than that.

01:58:09.000 --> 01:58:16.000
It's the .01 percent that own just huge amounts of wealth and make decisions for everyone else.

01:58:16.000 --> 01:58:20.000
And that's what we really should be addressing.

01:58:20.000 --> 01:58:25.000
Are there differences you think? I mean there's obviously the technological differences.

01:58:25.000 --> 01:58:30.000
But what kinds of... If you're talking about the organizing you did in Mississippi when you started.

01:58:30.000 --> 01:58:40.000
And the organizing needs to be done today. How would you talk to young people today about that and what they might do?

01:58:40.000 --> 01:58:44.000
Well actually some young people really get involved. It's nice.

01:58:44.000 --> 01:58:48.000
There was a generation when I go to political events.

01:58:48.000 --> 01:58:58.000
There was a generation that is younger than I am. But not the kids that are coming out of high school and just getting into college.

01:58:58.000 --> 01:59:04.000
There was a time if you go to those meetings. There's this old folks and young folks.

01:59:04.000 --> 01:59:10.000
And there was a time when there were these people... There was a generation that weren't involved.

01:59:10.000 --> 01:59:19.000
I actually fault us, the older folks who were involved, because we didn't teach our kids to be active.

01:59:19.000 --> 01:59:25.000
I mean if we'd have spent so much time ensuring our kids were activists.

01:59:25.000 --> 01:59:34.000
I know so many people whose children and would use Jean Wiley because she's mentioned.

01:59:34.000 --> 01:59:42.000
She's got a kid, he's not in politics. And these kids were brought up around politics but not...

01:59:42.000 --> 01:59:48.000
They weren't given the fire and the bell had to be involved. I think some of that's changing.

01:59:48.000 --> 01:59:56.000
In terms of kids are certainly well more informed now than... I mean they know stuff.

01:59:56.000 --> 02:00:00.000
Not just about sex but about politics, about international.

02:00:00.000 --> 02:00:05.000
You can't find a kid probably in the D.C. area that doesn't know more about Africa.

02:00:05.000 --> 02:00:11.000
When they're 12 then I did when I was 21 or Central America.

02:00:11.000 --> 02:00:20.000
I mean so there's information there but there's also a great push to keep people from pushing for change.

02:00:20.000 --> 02:00:27.000
And I think that's always been there and sponsored by the large corporations.

02:00:27.000 --> 02:00:33.000
The 1% or the 0.01%.

02:00:33.000 --> 02:00:41.000
That control the media and help and try and foster decisions on other people.

02:00:41.000 --> 02:00:44.000
They've gotten more sophisticated at that.

02:00:44.000 --> 02:00:50.000
So it's a different battle and we just have to try and figure out.

02:00:50.000 --> 02:00:55.000
Again just fight it one step at a time.

02:00:55.000 --> 02:01:02.000
Thank you for the other things that we should touch on.

02:01:02.000 --> 02:01:07.000
No I just hope kids continue getting involved.

02:01:07.000 --> 02:01:11.000
Do you talk to students, classrooms at all?

02:01:11.000 --> 02:01:17.000
I don't talk in classrooms. I talk a lot one on one. I talk... I don't go into classrooms.

02:01:17.000 --> 02:01:24.000
I notice that none of the SNCC people at the conference at the 50th anniversary are doing classroom work.

02:01:24.000 --> 02:01:31.000
I do some. There have been a couple of events they've asked me to speak at them.

02:01:31.000 --> 02:01:37.000
You use larger events. But I don't... you know and it's what it was like.

02:01:37.000 --> 02:01:44.000
And I tell them it's not what it was like, it's what it is like.

02:01:44.000 --> 02:01:48.000
Yeah I think going into classrooms would help.

02:01:49.000 --> 02:01:59.000
I like to think that I try to work on issues that will get attention politically or in the media that will reach more people.

02:01:59.000 --> 02:02:05.000
And I certainly credit teachers who are out there day after day.

02:02:05.000 --> 02:02:10.000
Well thank you very much. We're talking with us.

02:02:10.000 --> 02:02:17.000
This has been a presentation of the library.
